1
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:29,240
'This film is dedicated to prisoners of war.

2
00:01:29,240 --> 00:01:33,080
'Their unbroken spirit is the symbol of a moral victory

3
00:01:33,080 --> 00:01:35,520
'for which no bells have pealed.

4
00:01:35,520 --> 00:01:37,320
'And which will not be remembered

5
00:01:37,320 --> 00:01:40,320
'with the battle names on regimental colours.

6
00:01:40,320 --> 00:01:43,800
'It was a war in which no decorations could be given,

7
00:01:43,800 --> 00:01:45,400
'but to have come out of it

8
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:49,400
'with a whole spirit is its highest honour.

9
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:51,640
'These are a few of those men

10
00:01:51,640 --> 00:01:54,240
'captured in the summer of 1940.

11
00:01:54,240 --> 00:01:56,320
'They were the men who stood on the Dial,

12
00:01:56,320 --> 00:01:58,360
'the Somme, and the La Basi Canal,

13
00:01:58,360 --> 00:02:00,960
'who fought at Calais, April, St Valery,

14
00:02:00,960 --> 00:02:05,240
'and the vital perimeter around the beaches of Dunkirk,

15
00:02:05,240 --> 00:02:10,040
'the men who held on until the German armour thundered past their lines.

16
00:02:10,040 --> 00:02:13,920
'220 miles they marched into captivity,

17
00:02:13,920 --> 00:02:18,200
'through that blazing, dusty June, through France, through Belgium,

18
00:02:18,200 --> 00:02:21,120
'through Holland, to the Rhine.'

19
00:03:10,520 --> 00:03:12,000
Ahh...

20
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:13,920
Beer isn't what it used to be.

21
00:03:13,920 --> 00:03:16,280
I hope the French beer isn't what it used to be, either.

22
00:03:16,280 --> 00:03:17,760
Remember the last time, Ted?

23
00:03:17,760 --> 00:03:20,120
Yeah, I remember something better than beer, too.

24
00:03:20,120 --> 00:03:23,200
That stunner! Ooh, she was a smasher.

25
00:03:23,200 --> 00:03:25,880
I can see her hair now, blacker than coal.

26
00:03:25,880 --> 00:03:27,320
And that savoury piece in Lille!

27
00:03:27,320 --> 00:03:29,760
Ooh, boy! She taught me a thing or two.

28
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:31,680
Pity you kept it to yourself.

29
00:03:31,680 --> 00:03:35,000
It's proud we should be married to a couple of Don Juans.

30
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,400
Don't believe a girl ever looked at him twice. Poor old dear.

31
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:41,240
- Steady, you looked twice, didn't you? 
- You caught me off me guard.

32
00:03:41,240 --> 00:03:43,680
I was low following the flu.

33
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:45,560
Wonder what made you marry me.

34
00:03:45,560 --> 00:03:48,480
You don't know? That wicked tenor voice you have.

35
00:03:48,480 --> 00:03:51,160
- Leave them. Me and Ted will clear later. 
- Any more for any more?

36
00:03:51,160 --> 00:03:54,360
- No, thank you. 
- It's nearly 12. We've got to be at the depot at 7am.

37
00:03:54,360 --> 00:03:57,560
- Come on home. 
- We'll have 'em both back before you can turn round.

38
00:03:57,560 --> 00:03:59,040
War will be over by Christmas.

39
00:03:59,040 --> 00:04:01,800
War will be over by Christmas? Where have I heard that before?

40
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:04,200
It's a shame we got to close the business.

41
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:07,200
It's just a habit we've got into, fighting the same war every 20 years.

42
00:04:07,200 --> 00:04:09,560
- Nasty habit, too. 
- Good night, Flo.

43
00:04:09,560 --> 00:04:11,040
Good night.

44
00:04:11,040 --> 00:04:12,440
See you in the morning.

45
00:04:12,440 --> 00:04:13,640
All right.

46
00:04:13,640 --> 00:04:15,320
She's a proper worrier.

47
00:04:15,320 --> 00:04:16,920
Shame she never had kids.

48
00:04:16,920 --> 00:04:18,720
And her always wanting them so much.

49
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:20,600
They'd have took her mind off things.

50
00:04:20,600 --> 00:04:22,840
Well, it's too late now, I suppose.

51
00:04:22,840 --> 00:04:25,720
Are you sorry Glad and Mary are grown up?

52
00:04:25,720 --> 00:04:28,800
Well, I am and I'm not, in a manner of speaking.

53
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:31,320
What about starting all over again, old girl?

54
00:04:31,320 --> 00:04:33,080
No, thank you, Ted.

55
00:04:33,080 --> 00:04:35,000
I'm too old for that kind of war work.

56
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:36,480
HE CHUCKLES

57
00:05:05,520 --> 00:05:07,760
DRAMATIC PIANO MUSIC

58
00:06:01,200 --> 00:06:04,320
- Thanks, Stephen. I liked that a lot. 
- The boy definitely shows promise.

59
00:06:04,320 --> 00:06:07,000
- Nearly 1 o'clock. 
- May I cadge a lift? 
- Yes, of course.

60
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:08,600
Come on, Carol. Put your bonnet on.

61
00:06:08,600 --> 00:06:11,160
- Cheerio. See you before you embark. 
- Righty-o, Robert.

62
00:06:11,160 --> 00:06:13,880
- Goodbye, Stephen, darling. Take care of yourself. 
- Good night.

63
00:06:13,880 --> 00:06:15,360
Well, wait for me.

64
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:19,640
(Stephen...)

65
00:06:19,640 --> 00:06:21,560
Come on, Carol!

66
00:06:21,560 --> 00:06:24,000
All right, Robert!

67
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:25,920
(Caroline...)

68
00:06:30,200 --> 00:06:32,640
Caroline! Caroline!

69
00:06:32,640 --> 00:06:36,320
CAR DRIVES AWAY

70
00:06:40,280 --> 00:06:42,280
Stephen...

71
00:06:42,280 --> 00:06:43,920
Caroline!

72
00:06:46,040 --> 00:06:48,480
You left your scarf.

73
00:06:49,880 --> 00:06:52,280
I know.

74
00:06:52,280 --> 00:06:54,200
I had to come back.

75
00:06:54,200 --> 00:06:55,640
Robert. What about him?

76
00:06:55,640 --> 00:06:57,560
I wanted to tell you.

77
00:06:57,560 --> 00:07:00,400
It's all over with Robert.

78
00:07:00,400 --> 00:07:03,360
I think he understands.

79
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:05,280
I told him three weeks ago.

80
00:07:05,280 --> 00:07:07,200
We met three weeks ago.

81
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:11,080
I wasn't sure until tonight.

82
00:07:12,440 --> 00:07:14,000
Caroline.

83
00:07:23,480 --> 00:07:27,320
You've only 48 hours before you go to France.

84
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:31,640
It's nothing and it's everything.

85
00:07:31,640 --> 00:07:33,080
Everything.

86
00:07:33,080 --> 00:07:36,000
I hope you know how to get a special licence.

87
00:08:14,360 --> 00:08:16,520
TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS

88
00:08:20,680 --> 00:08:22,600
HUBBUB

89
00:08:22,600 --> 00:08:25,000
- And don't forget to write, David. 
- Yes, Mum.

90
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:26,880
Let us know if there's anything you want.

91
00:08:26,880 --> 00:08:29,320
Thank you, Mrs McDougall. Will you write to me, Elspeth?

92
00:08:29,320 --> 00:08:31,600
- Yes, David, I will. 
- You see, I...

93
00:08:31,600 --> 00:08:33,560
WHISTLE BLOWS

94
00:08:35,480 --> 00:08:36,960
Yes, David?

95
00:08:36,960 --> 00:08:39,320
- Goodbye, David. 
- Goodbye, David, my boy.

96
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:40,800
Goodbye, Mother.

97
00:08:40,800 --> 00:08:42,200
Take care of yourself, David.

98
00:08:42,200 --> 00:08:44,760
- Yes, Mrs McDougall. Elspeth, you see, I... 
- Me too, David.

99
00:08:44,760 --> 00:08:46,040
What did you say?

100
00:08:46,040 --> 00:08:47,480
I love you.

101
00:08:47,480 --> 00:08:50,000
Elspeth. Elspeth, will you marry me?

102
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:51,360
Yes, David!

103
00:08:53,560 --> 00:08:55,960
TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS

104
00:09:06,280 --> 00:09:08,800
CHURCH BELLS TOLL

105
00:09:30,440 --> 00:09:33,040
Macht schnell! Los, los, schnell!

106
00:09:33,040 --> 00:09:34,960
MAN COUNTS IN GERMAN

107
00:09:40,280 --> 00:09:41,880
Mehr Tempo!

108
00:09:45,280 --> 00:09:48,440
Herr Major, dass die Offiziere von den Mannschaften getrennt werden.

109
00:09:48,440 --> 00:09:49,880
What's he talking about?

110
00:09:49,880 --> 00:09:51,400
Sorry. I've no idea.

111
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:53,440
Can I be of any help?

112
00:09:53,440 --> 00:09:55,080
Do you speak German? Good.

113
00:09:56,720 --> 00:10:00,840
Herr Major hat Sie nicht verstanden. Kann ich ubersetzen, was Sie zu sagen wunschen?

114
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:04,760
Ja, gut. Erklaren Sie, dass die Offiziere von den Mannschaften getrennt werden.

115
00:10:04,760 --> 00:10:08,000
He says the officers must be separated from the men.

116
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:10,040
But we must keep the wounded with us.

117
00:10:10,040 --> 00:10:12,440
We've only got one MO among the lot of us.

118
00:10:12,440 --> 00:10:16,520
Der Herr Major bittet, dass wir auf jeden Fall unsere Verwundeten bei uns behalten koennen.

119
00:10:16,520 --> 00:10:18,280
Wir haben nur einen Arzt fuer uns alle.

120
00:10:18,280 --> 00:10:22,560
Nun gut. Dann koennen Sie vorlaeufig zusammen bleiben bis Sie ins Lager transportiert werden.

121
00:10:22,560 --> 00:10:25,480
- He says they may stay with us till we reach the camp. 
- Thank you.

122
00:10:25,480 --> 00:10:29,240
- A lot of them will remain automatically on the orderlies' train. 
- That's right.

123
00:10:29,240 --> 00:10:30,720
Well, come on, lads. In we go.

124
00:10:47,960 --> 00:10:50,360
- How's tricks, Evans? 
- Mustn't grumble, sir.

125
00:10:50,360 --> 00:10:53,200
- You'll feel better with a gasper. 
- Thank you, sir.

126
00:10:53,200 --> 00:10:55,160
HE COUGHS

127
00:10:55,160 --> 00:10:57,400
I don't know that you ought to smoke with that chest.

128
00:10:57,400 --> 00:10:59,520
Oh, it's nothing. Wound's practically healed.

129
00:10:59,520 --> 00:11:01,400
It's a pretty bad show all around.

130
00:11:01,400 --> 00:11:03,800
I take it you fellows feel the same as I do.

131
00:11:03,800 --> 00:11:06,360
We mustn't let the Jerries see we're down.

132
00:11:06,360 --> 00:11:08,920
Take the Jerries to get me down? It's them ruddy cobbles.

133
00:11:08,920 --> 00:11:11,000
What can I do for my feet, sir?

134
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:12,920
Do what I do. Try to forget 'em.

135
00:11:12,920 --> 00:11:14,400
I can't take 'em off, can I?

136
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:16,720
How are you, Lennox? Eyes hurting you a bit?

137
00:11:16,720 --> 00:11:18,240
A wee bit, sir.

138
00:11:18,240 --> 00:11:22,040
We'll get the Jerries to give you some proper treatment As soon as we reach camp.

139
00:11:22,040 --> 00:11:24,920
- Thank you, sir. 
- How about you?

140
00:11:24,920 --> 00:11:26,840
Mustn't grumble.

141
00:11:26,840 --> 00:11:28,760
- You OK? 
- Not too bad.

142
00:11:28,760 --> 00:11:30,680
- How's the arm? 
- Feels better now, sir.

143
00:11:30,680 --> 00:11:32,320
Good boy. All right, lads.

144
00:11:32,320 --> 00:11:34,080
It won't be long now.

145
00:11:34,080 --> 00:11:36,960
Then you'll be able to have a real rest.

146
00:11:36,960 --> 00:11:38,880
Thanks for the help just now.

147
00:11:38,880 --> 00:11:40,760
Useful man to know. Perfect German.

148
00:11:40,760 --> 00:11:43,440
Dalrymple's my name. 31st Lancers.

149
00:11:43,440 --> 00:11:46,200
Geoffrey Mitchell, 5th Oxfordshire light infantry.

150
00:11:46,200 --> 00:11:48,360
Oh, where did the Jerries pick you up?

151
00:11:48,360 --> 00:11:49,920
Thionville.

152
00:11:49,920 --> 00:11:53,760
- Oh, really? I didn't know the 5th were anywhere near there. 
- Yes.

153
00:11:53,760 --> 00:11:55,320
Oh!

154
00:12:17,600 --> 00:12:19,560
GUNFIRE

155
00:12:21,560 --> 00:12:23,920
EXPLOSIONS

156
00:13:23,520 --> 00:13:26,040
TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS

157
00:13:52,640 --> 00:13:54,880
GERMAN SOLDIERS BARK ORDERS

158
00:14:10,680 --> 00:14:12,280
March to attention!

159
00:14:19,640 --> 00:14:21,480
MEN START WHISTLING

160
00:14:26,320 --> 00:14:28,600
ALL WHISTLE TUNE TOGETHER

161
00:15:06,160 --> 00:15:09,040
CLOCK CHIMES HOUR

162
00:15:18,720 --> 00:15:20,120
Good afternoon.

163
00:15:20,120 --> 00:15:22,560
Good afternoon. Do sit down, won't you?

164
00:15:22,560 --> 00:15:23,960
Thank you.

165
00:15:23,960 --> 00:15:25,880
My name's Celia Mitchell.

166
00:15:25,880 --> 00:15:28,320
I've heard my husband may be a prisoner of war...

167
00:15:28,320 --> 00:15:29,720
Captain Geoffrey Mitchell.

168
00:15:29,720 --> 00:15:32,600
Maybe. Didn't the war office notify you, Mrs Mitchell?

169
00:15:32,600 --> 00:15:35,960
Well, no, you see, I don't expect he put me down as next of kin.

170
00:15:35,960 --> 00:15:37,880
Oh, I beg your pardon.

171
00:15:37,880 --> 00:15:39,360
Your husband's regiment?

172
00:15:39,360 --> 00:15:40,760
5th Oxford light infantry.

173
00:15:40,760 --> 00:15:44,600
General index. Give me particulars of Captain Geoffrey Mitchell,

174
00:15:44,600 --> 00:15:46,520
5th Oxfordshire light infantry, will you?

175
00:15:46,520 --> 00:15:48,000
I'd like to send him parcels.

176
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:49,400
I suppose I can do that.

177
00:15:49,400 --> 00:15:50,840
Oh, yes, certainly.

178
00:15:50,840 --> 00:15:54,680
Flag 27. Prisoner of war number 1376.

179
00:15:54,680 --> 00:15:56,160
Thank you.

180
00:16:04,280 --> 00:16:05,760
Hello, Mummy!

181
00:16:05,760 --> 00:16:08,600
Hello, darling. Have you had a lovely day with Grandpa?

182
00:16:08,600 --> 00:16:10,520
Will Father ever come back to us, Grandpa,

183
00:16:10,520 --> 00:16:12,440
even when the war's over?

184
00:16:12,440 --> 00:16:14,360
Well, would you be glad if he did?

185
00:16:14,360 --> 00:16:16,280
No. He used to make Mummy cry.

186
00:16:16,280 --> 00:16:17,560
He is a prisoner.

187
00:16:17,560 --> 00:16:19,680
- Hello, Desmond. 
- Hello, Mummy.

188
00:16:19,680 --> 00:16:22,080
Janet, I'll leave you in charge.

189
00:16:27,360 --> 00:16:28,760
Well?

190
00:16:28,760 --> 00:16:31,680
He didn't put me down as next of kin.

191
00:16:37,440 --> 00:16:40,760
Well, that seems to be the final gesture, doesn't it, my dear?

192
00:16:40,760 --> 00:16:43,200
It was only logical, I suppose.

193
00:16:43,200 --> 00:16:44,520
Poor Geoffrey.

194
00:16:44,520 --> 00:16:46,040
Poor Geoffrey?

195
00:16:46,040 --> 00:16:49,400
Well, I for one don't intend to shed any tears over him.

196
00:16:49,400 --> 00:16:50,840
- Father? 
- Hmm?

197
00:16:50,840 --> 00:16:52,760
I'm going to write to him.

198
00:16:52,760 --> 00:16:55,200
- You are? 
- Yes.

199
00:16:55,200 --> 00:16:57,120
Can't do any harm or good.

200
00:16:57,120 --> 00:16:59,240
They must be glad of any news of home.

201
00:16:59,240 --> 00:17:02,880
I don't suppose Geoffrey ever betrayed the faintest interest in his home.

202
00:17:02,880 --> 00:17:05,240
I can tell him how the children are getting on.

203
00:17:05,240 --> 00:17:08,120
I can see Geoffrey regaling his fellow prisoners

204
00:17:08,120 --> 00:17:11,000
with news of the children he's scarcely ever seen.

205
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:12,920
You're afraid, aren't you, Father?

206
00:17:12,920 --> 00:17:16,440
Certainly. I'm afraid that you may let yourself be carried away

207
00:17:16,440 --> 00:17:19,680
by sentimentality and suggest patching things up with him.

208
00:17:19,680 --> 00:17:21,240
Don't worry.

209
00:17:21,240 --> 00:17:24,440
But we said so many hard, cruel things to each other.

210
00:17:24,440 --> 00:17:26,360
I'd like to wipe out the memory of them.

211
00:17:26,360 --> 00:17:28,760
And then if we should happen to meet when the war's over,

212
00:17:28,760 --> 00:17:30,720
it won't be as enemies.

213
00:17:50,600 --> 00:17:52,760
Here. Go easy with the soap.

214
00:17:52,760 --> 00:17:54,240
Sorry, old boy.

215
00:17:54,240 --> 00:17:57,120
We may make it last two days more if we're very careful.

216
00:17:57,120 --> 00:18:00,000
After that, we've got to make do with godliness.

217
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,880
I say, Padre, what are you smoking? Sauerkraut?

218
00:18:02,880 --> 00:18:04,760
Fag ends of fag ends of fag ends.

219
00:18:04,760 --> 00:18:07,600
Lucky fellow. I'm down to Mr Middleton's specials.

220
00:18:07,600 --> 00:18:09,160
Not a cough in a contest.

221
00:18:09,160 --> 00:18:12,760
I hear there's a bush around here that's not too bad in a pipe.

222
00:18:12,760 --> 00:18:14,360
Had a marvellous dream last night.

223
00:18:14,360 --> 00:18:15,840
Anybody I know?

224
00:18:15,840 --> 00:18:17,240
Eggs and bacon.

225
00:18:17,240 --> 00:18:19,480
Tomato ketchup this time.

226
00:18:19,480 --> 00:18:21,560
We must have lost a shocking lot of stuff.

227
00:18:21,560 --> 00:18:22,960
There's nothing to stop 'em.

228
00:18:22,960 --> 00:18:25,880
He's bound to invade before the end of summer, that's the end of us.

229
00:18:25,880 --> 00:18:28,760
- Steady. What about the home fleet? 
- What about the Luftwaffe?!

230
00:18:28,760 --> 00:18:30,200
Well, of all the damn defeatists!

231
00:18:30,200 --> 00:18:33,080
- Well, if you prefer to be a ruddy halfwit. 
- What about the RAF?

232
00:18:33,080 --> 00:18:34,720
Hitler can't stage an invasion

233
00:18:34,720 --> 00:18:36,480
until he's got control of the air,

234
00:18:36,480 --> 00:18:39,800
- and I don't see the boys handing him that on a plate. 
- Hear, hear!

235
00:18:39,800 --> 00:18:42,080
You can't judge Hitler by ordinary standards.

236
00:18:42,080 --> 00:18:44,800
If he thinks he'll invade, he'll invade.

237
00:18:51,400 --> 00:18:54,360
My old woman makes the kids pay a penny a week for the Red Cross.

238
00:18:54,360 --> 00:18:56,360
I'm writing to her to stop that caper.

239
00:18:56,360 --> 00:18:58,000
Red ruddy Cross!

240
00:18:58,000 --> 00:18:59,880
Bloody sausage we ever get out of it!

241
00:18:59,880 --> 00:19:01,360
It's only two months.

242
00:19:01,360 --> 00:19:05,160
Don't forget, there were only a few hundred prisoners here before.

243
00:19:05,160 --> 00:19:06,600
Now there are tens of thousands.

244
00:19:06,600 --> 00:19:07,880
It's a big job.

245
00:19:07,880 --> 00:19:09,480
Yeah. Don't let's kid ourselves.

246
00:19:09,480 --> 00:19:11,120
Nobody worries about us anymore.

247
00:19:11,120 --> 00:19:12,880
We've been written off.

248
00:19:12,880 --> 00:19:14,800
You're a pessimist.

249
00:19:14,800 --> 00:19:16,360
How do you spell "sufficient"?

250
00:19:16,360 --> 00:19:20,040
Same as the Sergeant Major's blessing, two "F"s and one "C".

251
00:19:20,040 --> 00:19:21,480
Writing about the grub.

252
00:19:21,480 --> 00:19:22,920
Muck, I call it.

253
00:19:22,920 --> 00:19:25,640
Bit of the old woman's cooking is what I'd like now.

254
00:19:25,640 --> 00:19:28,120
What a sucker I was joining the ruddy army.

255
00:19:28,120 --> 00:19:31,080
Picturing meself cutting loose with some rowdy old French dames.

256
00:19:31,080 --> 00:19:33,960
Here I am shut up in this place till I'll be past it.

257
00:19:33,960 --> 00:19:36,840
You ought to have joined the Navy and let the world see you.

258
00:19:36,840 --> 00:19:38,760
Now, son, there's no use you blowing off.

259
00:19:38,760 --> 00:19:41,840
Take things as you find them, that's always been my motto.

260
00:19:41,840 --> 00:19:43,080
The way I look at it is...

261
00:19:43,080 --> 00:19:45,960
Hark at you! Drip, drip, drip. You're worse than a woman.

262
00:19:45,960 --> 00:19:47,880
Knock it, sonny. I was swinging a rifle

263
00:19:47,880 --> 00:19:49,360
when your nappies was on the line.

264
00:19:49,360 --> 00:19:51,280
Swinging a lead, more like it.

265
00:19:51,280 --> 00:19:54,600
Here, if you want a clip on the ear, my lad, you've come to the right person.

266
00:19:54,600 --> 00:19:55,840
Ohh!

267
00:19:55,840 --> 00:19:58,200
- That cigarette. Let me see it. 
- What do you mean see it?

268
00:19:58,200 --> 00:19:59,880
It's a Player's. Where did you get it?

269
00:19:59,880 --> 00:20:01,320
Saved it up. What's it to you?

270
00:20:01,320 --> 00:20:04,000
- I had three Player's left. You stole it! 
- Ah, go chase yourself.

271
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:07,120
- Hand it over! 
- Pipe down, you little Welshman. 
- Give it back!

272
00:20:14,800 --> 00:20:17,160
You did pinch that fag, you young basket.

273
00:20:17,160 --> 00:20:18,600
Yes, I did. So what?

274
00:20:18,600 --> 00:20:20,480
- Just this. 
- Ooh!

275
00:20:22,440 --> 00:20:24,120
Been asking for it, sonny.

276
00:20:24,120 --> 00:20:28,720
I'm a man of peace, and peace is what I'm going to have plenty of in here.

277
00:20:28,720 --> 00:20:31,800
Blimey. They'll have to have you at the peace conference.

278
00:20:31,800 --> 00:20:34,480
- How are you today, Jessup? 
- Mustn't grumble, sir.

279
00:20:34,480 --> 00:20:36,840
- Manage to get any sleep? 
- Not so as you'd notice.

280
00:20:36,840 --> 00:20:38,280
We'll soon get you out of here.

281
00:20:38,280 --> 00:20:40,240
Yes, sir. Thank you, sir.

282
00:20:43,080 --> 00:20:45,000
Morning, Lennox.

283
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:46,280
Oh, good morning, sir.

284
00:20:46,280 --> 00:20:47,760
Got some good news for you, David.

285
00:20:47,760 --> 00:20:49,160
Yes, Padre?

286
00:20:49,160 --> 00:20:51,720
Yes, my lad. You'll be rejoining the rest of us tomorrow.

287
00:20:51,720 --> 00:20:53,200
Oh, that's fine, sir.

288
00:20:53,200 --> 00:20:55,560
And I'll be able to take this bandage off?

289
00:20:55,560 --> 00:20:57,080
Not yet, I'm afraid.

290
00:20:57,080 --> 00:21:00,040
You'll have to wait till the optic nerve is completely healthy again.

291
00:21:00,040 --> 00:21:02,520
They'll send you to the eye hospital for an operation.

292
00:21:02,520 --> 00:21:05,200
So you'll have to be a very patient patient, my boy.

293
00:21:05,200 --> 00:21:07,120
I'll do my best, sir.

294
00:21:08,520 --> 00:21:10,000
That's right.

295
00:21:13,880 --> 00:21:15,720
I'm sorry, mate. I'll give you a packet of 20

296
00:21:15,720 --> 00:21:17,640
when the Red Cross parcels come.

297
00:21:17,640 --> 00:21:19,560
Losing my temper over a fag.

298
00:21:19,560 --> 00:21:21,480
I shouldn't have left them loafing about.

299
00:21:21,480 --> 00:21:24,000
You know, you wouldn't be a bad lad,

300
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:25,840
if you got rid of some of your nasty habits.

301
00:21:25,840 --> 00:21:28,720
Nark it. Leave all that reforming stuff to the padre.

302
00:21:28,720 --> 00:21:31,080
What's your job in Civvy Street?

303
00:21:31,080 --> 00:21:32,520
Only suckers work.

304
00:21:32,520 --> 00:21:34,920
- Oh, a wide boy, eh? 
- You bet.

305
00:21:34,920 --> 00:21:37,320
Me and Ted's in the building business.

306
00:21:37,320 --> 00:21:39,720
What about learning the trade when we get home?

307
00:21:39,720 --> 00:21:41,640
I'll be home long before you two mugs.

308
00:21:41,640 --> 00:21:43,080
I'm going to scarper.

309
00:21:43,080 --> 00:21:45,000
You got out of tougher spots than this, eh?

310
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:46,920
- Sure. 
- Got a plan?

311
00:21:46,920 --> 00:21:49,360
Dozens of 'em. For instance...

312
00:21:49,360 --> 00:21:51,280
You know, I can't make up me mind

313
00:21:51,280 --> 00:21:54,040
whether to turn this into a brigantine or a schooner.

314
00:21:56,440 --> 00:21:58,480
GIRL GIGGLES

315
00:22:01,800 --> 00:22:04,240
I wonder how Jane's getting on these days?

316
00:22:04,240 --> 00:22:05,640
Who is Jane?

317
00:22:05,640 --> 00:22:07,120
Your girl?

318
00:22:07,120 --> 00:22:10,000
No, no, the Jane, the strip in the Mirror.

319
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:12,360
Oh, yes, the strip in the Mirror.

320
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:15,080
I suppose a highbrow like you wouldn't read the Daily Mirror.

321
00:22:15,080 --> 00:22:17,760
Oh, I don't know. Why highbrow?

322
00:22:17,760 --> 00:22:20,080
I mean, perfect German and all that sort of thing.

323
00:22:20,080 --> 00:22:22,000
Spent much time in Germany?

324
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:24,360
Yes, as a matter of fact, I have.

325
00:22:24,360 --> 00:22:26,240
Come to think of it, it's funny that

326
00:22:26,240 --> 00:22:29,160
- none of the rest of your chaps got caught with you. 
- Yes.

327
00:22:29,160 --> 00:22:30,760
Did you have a company?

328
00:22:30,760 --> 00:22:32,040
Yes, machine gun company.

329
00:22:32,040 --> 00:22:33,520
Machine gun company?!

330
00:22:35,400 --> 00:22:36,840
You see, I...

331
00:22:36,840 --> 00:22:39,280
I think I'll turn it up. Wound's hurting a bit.

332
00:22:44,560 --> 00:22:48,840
All I have to do is stow away in one of them garbage bins or something, why, it's as easy as...

333
00:22:48,840 --> 00:22:51,520
If you're planning an escape, Mathews,

334
00:22:51,520 --> 00:22:53,160
may I give you a piece of advice?

335
00:22:53,160 --> 00:22:55,080
Individual escapes hardly ever succeed.

336
00:22:55,080 --> 00:22:58,600
These things have to be planned and coordinated by a whole group.

337
00:22:58,600 --> 00:23:02,280
All the same, sir, I'm going to have a go at it if you have no objections.

338
00:23:02,280 --> 00:23:04,240
Well, good luck to you.

339
00:23:06,480 --> 00:23:08,600
Good luck. Two-faced bleeder.

340
00:23:08,600 --> 00:23:11,880
I don't know what it is, but there's something phony about that bloke.

341
00:23:11,880 --> 00:23:14,600
Always sucking up with the German MO or Commandant.

342
00:23:14,600 --> 00:23:16,480
Look, men!

343
00:23:19,560 --> 00:23:22,000
That settles it.

344
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:24,440
But they have machine gun companies in the German army.

345
00:23:24,440 --> 00:23:27,920
- You seriously think he's a traitor? 
- He speaks German as well as any German.

346
00:23:27,920 --> 00:23:30,320
Why shouldn't he be a German planted here as a stool pigeon?

347
00:23:30,320 --> 00:23:33,880
- That would account for a lot of things. 
- We're always talking about home. He never does.

348
00:23:33,880 --> 00:23:36,360
- I hate to believe it. 
- Come in.

349
00:23:36,360 --> 00:23:38,480
May I report something, sir?

350
00:23:38,480 --> 00:23:39,600
Go ahead.

351
00:23:39,600 --> 00:23:41,360
Well, it's rather confidential, sir.

352
00:23:41,360 --> 00:23:43,680
It's about somebody we think's a fifth columnist.

353
00:23:43,680 --> 00:23:45,960
- An officer? 
- A matter of fact, sir, it is.

354
00:23:45,960 --> 00:23:47,160
Captain Mitchell, sir.

355
00:23:47,160 --> 00:23:49,800
- There you are. 
- He overheard me planning a breakout

356
00:23:49,800 --> 00:23:52,680
- and went and talked to one of the German guards. 
- Thank you.

357
00:23:52,680 --> 00:23:56,000
- Keep your mouth shut for the time being. 
- Very good, sir.

358
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:58,320
There's only one thing to do with a rat. String him up!

359
00:23:58,320 --> 00:24:00,840
Here, wait a bit. Man's innocent till he's proved guilty.

360
00:24:00,840 --> 00:24:02,760
Don't let us behave like a bunch of Nazis.

361
00:24:02,760 --> 00:24:04,120
Come on.

362
00:24:08,440 --> 00:24:12,040
Oh, Mitchell, you didn't destroy your identity card, did you?

363
00:24:12,040 --> 00:24:13,120
No, why?

364
00:24:13,120 --> 00:24:15,280
Oh, just check up. Have a look at it?

365
00:24:25,600 --> 00:24:27,640
Do you mind duplicating your signature?

366
00:24:33,040 --> 00:24:35,440
You can't do it, you swine, your name isn't Mitchell!

367
00:24:35,440 --> 00:24:38,160
- Come on, what are we waiting for? Let's get it over with! 
- Stop it!

368
00:24:38,160 --> 00:24:40,520
If you have anything to say, you better say it quick.

369
00:24:40,520 --> 00:24:41,680
It's a long story, and...

370
00:24:43,720 --> 00:24:45,440
..you wouldn't believe a word of it.

371
00:24:45,440 --> 00:24:47,880
- You're dead right, we wouldn't! 
- Shut up! Go on, spill it.

372
00:24:48,960 --> 00:24:50,680
I'm not a German. I'm a Czech.

373
00:24:50,680 --> 00:24:53,160
A Czech in British uniform? That's bloody likely!

374
00:24:53,160 --> 00:24:55,880
I'm in charge here. Shut up, and that's an order!

375
00:24:55,880 --> 00:24:57,400
Come on.

376
00:24:57,400 --> 00:24:59,520
I escaped from a German concentration camp.

377
00:24:59,520 --> 00:25:01,800
I got through to France, and I took this uniform

378
00:25:01,800 --> 00:25:04,200
and the identity card from Mitchell's dead body.

379
00:25:04,200 --> 00:25:07,080
It was my only chance if the Germans caught up with me.

380
00:25:07,080 --> 00:25:09,000
If that's the truth, why didn't you tell us?

381
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:11,880
Would you have believed me any more than you do now?

382
00:25:11,880 --> 00:25:14,760
Besides, I have more to fear from the stool pigeons than you have.

383
00:25:14,760 --> 00:25:16,360
You've no proof of your story.

384
00:25:16,360 --> 00:25:18,160
None. How could I have?

385
00:25:18,160 --> 00:25:20,760
How do you come to speak such perfect English and German?

386
00:25:20,760 --> 00:25:24,120
My father was at the Czech embassy in London after the last war.

387
00:25:24,120 --> 00:25:25,320
I spent my childhood there.

388
00:25:25,320 --> 00:25:28,200
German is a sort of second language in Czechoslovakia.

389
00:25:28,200 --> 00:25:31,560
I became professor of English at Prague University.

390
00:25:31,560 --> 00:25:33,480
I'm not much of a soldier, I'm afraid.

391
00:25:33,480 --> 00:25:35,920
What were you talking about to that guard just now?

392
00:25:35,920 --> 00:25:39,760
Oh, I was trying to get a chess set for David Lennox.

393
00:25:39,760 --> 00:25:41,160
- PA: 
- 'Achtung! Achtung!

394
00:25:41,160 --> 00:25:43,480
'All British prisoners will parade at once.'

395
00:25:47,040 --> 00:25:49,800
- You may get proof of my story after all. 
- How?

396
00:25:49,800 --> 00:25:51,640
The civilian. His name's Forster.

397
00:25:51,640 --> 00:25:53,160
- Gestapo. 
- How do you know?

398
00:25:53,160 --> 00:25:55,080
He ran the concentration camp I was in.

399
00:25:55,080 --> 00:25:57,640
You think he'll recognise you?

400
00:25:57,640 --> 00:25:59,880
Well, if he does, he'll do your job for you.

401
00:25:59,880 --> 00:26:02,160
- 'Achtung! Achtung!' 
- Come on.

402
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:05,720
'All British prisoners will parade at once.'

403
00:26:05,720 --> 00:26:07,280
HE GREETS HIM IN GERMAN

404
00:26:09,040 --> 00:26:11,200
Right turn!

405
00:26:12,680 --> 00:26:14,800
Stand your men at ease, please.

406
00:26:16,240 --> 00:26:18,160
Stand at ease!

407
00:26:18,160 --> 00:26:22,160
Gentlemen, I present to you Herr Forster, the foreign office.

408
00:26:22,160 --> 00:26:25,760
Gentlemen. For the time being, all communications

409
00:26:25,760 --> 00:26:29,360
between Germany and England are at a standstill.

410
00:26:29,360 --> 00:26:32,240
Your letters, therefore, cannot leave this country.

411
00:26:32,240 --> 00:26:34,640
To keep you informed, however,

412
00:26:34,640 --> 00:26:38,800
our news bulletins will be broadcast to you in English.

413
00:26:38,800 --> 00:26:42,720
And as you cannot hope to receive news from home,

414
00:26:42,720 --> 00:26:44,560
arrangements have been made for you

415
00:26:44,560 --> 00:26:47,440
to broadcast messages to your next of kin.

416
00:26:47,440 --> 00:26:49,320
GRUMBLING

417
00:26:49,320 --> 00:26:52,360
Will all those who wish to avail themselves

418
00:26:52,360 --> 00:26:56,080
of Herr Forster's offer, take three paces forward!

419
00:27:14,320 --> 00:27:16,680
You are the senior British officer?

420
00:27:16,680 --> 00:27:21,480
- Yes. 
- Are your men afraid that this is some sort of propaganda trick?

421
00:27:21,480 --> 00:27:23,720
- Well, it's just possible. 
- As you wish.

422
00:27:26,760 --> 00:27:28,320
Your name?

423
00:27:28,320 --> 00:27:30,080
- Mitchell. 
- Mitchell?

424
00:27:30,080 --> 00:27:32,400
You are the officer acting as hospital interpreter.

425
00:27:32,400 --> 00:27:33,440
Yes.

426
00:27:33,440 --> 00:27:36,080
I understand you speak almost perfect German.

427
00:27:36,080 --> 00:27:38,120
That's rather unusual for an Englishman.

428
00:27:38,120 --> 00:27:41,840
- Is it? 
- I wonder why your face seems familiar.

429
00:27:41,840 --> 00:27:43,640
I have many friends in England.

430
00:27:43,640 --> 00:27:44,960
Possibly we met there.

431
00:27:44,960 --> 00:27:46,880
Possibly.

432
00:27:46,880 --> 00:27:49,000
Excuse me.

433
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:50,520
Yes?

434
00:27:52,480 --> 00:27:54,720
Do you wish to continue this conversation?

435
00:27:54,720 --> 00:27:58,240
- No. 
- Prisoners cannot be required to answer any questions

436
00:27:58,240 --> 00:28:00,320
other than relating to name, rank, and number.

437
00:28:00,320 --> 00:28:02,240
Quite, quite.

438
00:28:02,240 --> 00:28:04,200
The matter is of no importance.

439
00:28:09,280 --> 00:28:11,120
You may dismiss the parade.

440
00:28:12,840 --> 00:28:15,320
Parade, turn!

441
00:28:19,040 --> 00:28:21,360
- PA: 
- 'This is today's official war communique

442
00:28:21,360 --> 00:28:23,360
'issued by the German high command.

443
00:28:23,360 --> 00:28:27,200
'The Battle of Britain has entered upon a new and final stage.

444
00:28:27,200 --> 00:28:30,200
'Annihilation of England's towns and cities

445
00:28:30,200 --> 00:28:32,520
'by the all-conquering Luftwaffe.

446
00:28:32,520 --> 00:28:34,880
'Last night, just before sunset,

447
00:28:34,880 --> 00:28:37,960
'the air-raid sirens sounded their ominous wailing notes

448
00:28:37,960 --> 00:28:40,640
'to the 9 million inhabitants of Greater London.

449
00:28:40,640 --> 00:28:44,160
'All night, an endless stream of bombers roared above the city

450
00:28:44,160 --> 00:28:46,760
'discharging their loads of high-explosive

451
00:28:46,760 --> 00:28:48,360
'and incendiary bombs.

452
00:28:48,360 --> 00:28:51,680
'Anti-aircraft opposition was negligible,

453
00:28:51,680 --> 00:28:54,560
'for the British do not possess the guns to defend their homeland.

454
00:28:54,560 --> 00:28:58,880
'And this attack will continue every night from dusk till dawn

455
00:28:58,880 --> 00:29:03,240
'until the nerve centre and capital city of the British Empire

456
00:29:03,240 --> 00:29:07,080
'is reduced to a vast pile of rubble, dust, and ashes.

457
00:29:07,080 --> 00:29:10,800
'The words of our great battle hymn have come true at last.

458
00:29:10,800 --> 00:29:13,800
'Wir fahren gegen England!

459
00:29:13,800 --> 00:29:16,320
'We march against England!'

