Stephen wrote that for me.

505
00:32:25,280 --> 00:32:27,200
My application's been approved, Carol.

506
00:32:27,200 --> 00:32:29,120
Staff job, west Africa.

507
00:32:29,120 --> 00:32:31,520
I was going to ask you for a photograph,

508
00:32:31,520 --> 00:32:33,960
but perhaps I'm better without it.

509
00:32:33,960 --> 00:32:37,280
Look, Robert, ever since Beryl's been living here with me,

510
00:32:37,280 --> 00:32:39,200
I've seen how crazy she is about you.

511
00:32:39,200 --> 00:32:40,640
Why don't you and she...

512
00:32:40,640 --> 00:32:43,360
Beryl and I might have made a go of it

513
00:32:43,360 --> 00:32:44,640
if I hadn't met you first.

514
00:32:44,640 --> 00:32:45,920
I'm sorry, Robert.

515
00:32:45,920 --> 00:32:48,200
I did treat you shabbily.

516
00:32:48,200 --> 00:32:51,600
No, you didn't. I realise now you were never more than just fond of me.

517
00:32:51,600 --> 00:32:54,600
You'd have realised it, too, even if Stephen hadn't turned up.

518
00:32:54,600 --> 00:32:56,000
I always will be fond of you.

519
00:32:56,000 --> 00:32:58,880
As long as you're happy. That's what matters.

520
00:32:58,880 --> 00:33:00,800
That's sweet of you.

521
00:33:00,800 --> 00:33:02,240
My dear...

522
00:33:11,400 --> 00:33:13,320
I'm sorry.

523
00:33:13,320 --> 00:33:15,240
I'm not.

524
00:33:17,600 --> 00:33:21,000
But it's got to be goodbye, Robert.

525
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:22,440
Goodbye.

526
00:33:44,960 --> 00:33:47,520
Last Christmas, I had my first concert.

527
00:33:47,520 --> 00:33:49,800
It's there I met Caroline.

528
00:33:55,040 --> 00:33:58,880
Last Christmas, I was in Dachau concentration camp.

529
00:33:58,880 --> 00:34:02,720
Christmas eve, a new batch of prisoners came in.

530
00:34:02,720 --> 00:34:06,080
One of them brought me news of my family.

531
00:34:06,080 --> 00:34:09,920
They'd been caught giving food to a Polish Jew.

532
00:34:09,920 --> 00:34:12,320
They were taken out and shot.

533
00:34:14,080 --> 00:34:15,840
My father, my mother...

534
00:34:18,520 --> 00:34:19,720
All of them.

535
00:34:19,720 --> 00:34:21,440
Only 36 shopping days to Christmas.

536
00:34:21,440 --> 00:34:23,720
Christmas. Parked around a blazing fire

537
00:34:23,720 --> 00:34:25,280
with a great bowl of hot rum punch.

538
00:34:25,280 --> 00:34:28,200
Looks like it's snowing again. That should raise the temperature.

539
00:34:28,200 --> 00:34:30,120
What binds me is living by courtesy of Jerry.

540
00:34:30,120 --> 00:34:32,320
Can't see any future in it, really.

541
00:34:32,320 --> 00:34:34,400
They say the first seven years are the hardest.

542
00:34:34,400 --> 00:34:35,880
If the next six are like this...

543
00:34:35,880 --> 00:34:38,040
The Red Cross parcels are bound to arrive soon.

544
00:34:38,040 --> 00:34:43,040
- You've been saying that for exactly four months. 
- I've been meaning it!

545
00:34:43,040 --> 00:34:44,960
All I can think about is food.

546
00:34:44,960 --> 00:34:47,520
Roast turkey, mince pies, Christmas...

547
00:34:47,520 --> 00:34:48,600
Oh, shut up!

548
00:34:57,080 --> 00:34:59,840
Das ist alles.

549
00:34:59,840 --> 00:35:01,760
Well, lad, it's me again.

550
00:35:01,760 --> 00:35:03,240
Yes, padre.

551
00:35:04,640 --> 00:35:07,560
David, they can't operate.

552
00:35:09,480 --> 00:35:11,840
Not...ever?

553
00:35:11,840 --> 00:35:13,320
No, David.

554
00:35:15,840 --> 00:35:19,080
I won't ever see again?

555
00:35:20,480 --> 00:35:22,400
I don't believe it. It's that German doctor.

556
00:35:22,400 --> 00:35:24,840
- When I get back to Scotland... 
- No.

557
00:35:27,680 --> 00:35:30,600
David, it's no use. You've got to face it.

558
00:35:33,960 --> 00:35:35,880
I'll not need this anymore.

559
00:35:35,880 --> 00:35:38,720
You feel now there's nothing left to live for,

560
00:35:38,720 --> 00:35:42,560
and that feeling will go on for a long time,

561
00:35:42,560 --> 00:35:47,880
but then you'll begin to remember the things that are left.

562
00:35:47,880 --> 00:35:52,520
You'll begin to realise that this darkness of yours is not absolute.

563
00:35:52,520 --> 00:35:57,920
David, the things that make life worthwhile for all of us...

564
00:35:57,920 --> 00:36:02,240
kindness, affection, companionship...

565
00:36:02,240 --> 00:36:06,080
The loss of your sight can never rob you of those things, David.

566
00:36:06,080 --> 00:36:08,000
We're your friends here.

567
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:12,800
We offer you our help and understanding.

568
00:36:12,800 --> 00:36:15,680
And waiting to welcome you home

569
00:36:15,680 --> 00:36:21,000
when all this is over, are your own folk who love you.

570
00:36:25,760 --> 00:36:27,240
I'll be all right.

571
00:36:38,040 --> 00:36:40,240
HE SOBS

572
00:36:46,400 --> 00:36:50,440
18, 20, play 21s.

573
00:36:50,440 --> 00:36:53,120
- What's for tea? 
- Fancy cakes. Just fancy you've had 'em.

574
00:36:53,120 --> 00:36:55,520
Good job we haven't got any brass monkeys in here,

575
00:36:55,520 --> 00:36:58,400
we'd have the RSPCA down on us, and no error.

576
00:36:58,400 --> 00:37:01,000
Can't you do anything with this ruddy stove?

577
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:02,920
Isn't there anything else to burn?

578
00:37:08,960 --> 00:37:10,400
All right.

579
00:37:10,400 --> 00:37:12,760
I never said a word, did I?

580
00:37:12,760 --> 00:37:14,240
Go on, burn the ruddy thing.

581
00:37:14,240 --> 00:37:15,720
It's enough for a brew-up.

582
00:37:26,640 --> 00:37:28,640
They've come! Hundreds and hundreds of 'em!

583
00:37:28,640 --> 00:37:30,560
All right, I'll bite. Hundreds of what?

584
00:37:30,560 --> 00:37:32,440
Red Cross parcels, ruddy mountains of 'em!

585
00:37:32,440 --> 00:37:34,600
ALL SHOUT AND CHEER

586
00:37:39,680 --> 00:37:41,160
The Red Cross parcels are here!

587
00:37:41,160 --> 00:37:43,360
ALL: Hooray!

588
00:37:43,360 --> 00:37:45,000
Red Cross parcels are here!

589
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:46,920
ALL: Hooray!

590
00:38:20,520 --> 00:38:25,760
MEN SING: # O come all ye faithful

591
00:38:25,760 --> 00:38:30,080
# Joyful and triumphant

592
00:38:30,080 --> 00:38:35,120
# O come ye, O come ye

593
00:38:35,120 --> 00:38:39,680
# To Bethlehem

594
00:38:39,680 --> 00:38:44,480
# Come and behold him

595
00:38:44,480 --> 00:38:48,800
# Born the king of angels

596
00:38:48,800 --> 00:38:53,600
# O come let us adore him

597
00:38:53,600 --> 00:38:58,400
# O come let us adore him

598
00:38:58,400 --> 00:39:03,720
# O come let us adore him

599
00:39:03,720 --> 00:39:09,440
# Christ the Lord

600
00:39:09,440 --> 00:39:13,760
# Sing choirs of angels... #

601
00:39:13,760 --> 00:39:17,120
OC Sports, you. OC Music, Stephen Harley.

602
00:39:17,120 --> 00:39:19,840
- Anything else I haven't covered? 
- No. Extraordinary, isn't it?

603
00:39:19,840 --> 00:39:21,920
We seem to have specialists on every subject.

604
00:39:21,920 --> 00:39:24,360
Aren't you an expert on anything?

605
00:39:24,360 --> 00:39:25,760
Only racing, I'm afraid.

606
00:39:25,760 --> 00:39:28,160
I had thought of starting a little bookmaking business.

607
00:39:28,160 --> 00:39:31,040
Why not? Anyway, our money will be safe. You can't welsh on us.

608
00:39:31,040 --> 00:39:32,520
THEY LAUGH

609
00:39:44,040 --> 00:39:45,440
OK, number four shift.

610
00:39:45,440 --> 00:39:47,280
- How far? 
- About three feet.

611
00:39:47,280 --> 00:39:49,760
Good. By the way, doc, I put you down OC Entertainment.

612
00:39:49,760 --> 00:39:53,120
- Fine. 
- What about me? I've had masses of experience backstage.

613
00:39:53,120 --> 00:39:54,400
What sort of experience?

614
00:39:54,400 --> 00:39:57,440
No need to make low insinuendos, old man.

615
00:39:57,440 --> 00:39:58,920
Come on, fellows! Here it is!

616
00:39:58,920 --> 00:40:00,360
Mail from home!

617
00:40:01,800 --> 00:40:03,720
- Baker! 
- Here!

618
00:40:03,720 --> 00:40:06,160
- Macdonald! 
- Here!

619
00:40:06,160 --> 00:40:08,960
My father's been thrown through the dispensary window.

620
00:40:08,960 --> 00:40:10,880
What, by an angry patient?

621
00:40:10,880 --> 00:40:12,320
No, a bomb.

622
00:40:12,320 --> 00:40:14,640
Well, well, they've requisitioned the church hall.

623
00:40:14,640 --> 00:40:16,680
- I say, that's serious. 
- What is?

624
00:40:16,680 --> 00:40:18,600
Veronica. She sweats all night.

625
00:40:18,600 --> 00:40:20,520
Well, surely she can do something about it,

626
00:40:20,520 --> 00:40:22,960
- with all these advertisements. 
- Don't be a halfwit.

627
00:40:22,960 --> 00:40:25,320
Veronica's a filly and is getting ready for the flat.

628
00:40:25,320 --> 00:40:28,840
Oh, sorry, old boy. I thought she was a popsy getting ready for the...

629
00:40:28,840 --> 00:40:30,760
My kids have been evacuated to the country.

630
00:40:30,760 --> 00:40:32,760
My girl joined the land army. She'll wait for me

631
00:40:32,760 --> 00:40:34,880
- till the cows come home. 
- One way of putting it!

632
00:40:34,880 --> 00:40:37,320
Listen to this. "Dear Daddy, today is your birthday.

633
00:40:37,320 --> 00:40:39,720
"I hope it will be your last."

634
00:40:44,440 --> 00:40:45,920
Hello, David.

635
00:40:45,920 --> 00:40:49,320
- I didn't notice. Shall I read your letter for you? 
- Thank you.

636
00:40:51,200 --> 00:40:55,080
It's signed...Elspeth.

637
00:40:56,600 --> 00:40:57,960
"Dearest David,

638
00:40:57,960 --> 00:41:00,840
"your mother says I am silly to worry about it,

639
00:41:00,840 --> 00:41:04,640
"but it seems queer not a word from you yet.

640
00:41:04,640 --> 00:41:08,000
"Do please send me a line when you get this.

641
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:11,520
"The three of us had a little party on your birthday.

642
00:41:11,520 --> 00:41:13,280
"Wouldn't it be wonderful, darling,

643
00:41:13,280 --> 00:41:15,840
"if you were home again for your next?

644
00:41:15,840 --> 00:41:18,080
"I miss you all the time.

645
00:41:18,080 --> 00:41:20,000
"Your loving Elspeth.

646
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:24,800
"PS, I'm going to join the Wrens."

647
00:41:24,800 --> 00:41:26,240
Will you do me a favour?

648
00:41:26,240 --> 00:41:27,680
I'd like to answer it at once.

649
00:41:27,680 --> 00:41:29,120
Yes, of course.

650
00:41:29,120 --> 00:41:30,600
Here's a form.

651
00:41:30,600 --> 00:41:34,440
I've got a pencil. Ready when you are.

652
00:41:34,440 --> 00:41:37,320
My dearest Elspeth,

653
00:41:37,320 --> 00:41:41,400
I am dictating this letter because my wound

654
00:41:41,400 --> 00:41:44,000
is not quite better yet.

655
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:46,840
I've been thinking things over.

656
00:41:46,840 --> 00:41:51,200
And this is to ask if you will release me

657
00:41:51,200 --> 00:41:54,120
from our engagement.

658
00:41:54,120 --> 00:41:58,200
I realise now I don't feel the way

659
00:41:58,200 --> 00:42:02,720
I...I fancied I did about you.

660
00:42:02,720 --> 00:42:06,560
So it's best to make a definite break.

661
00:42:06,560 --> 00:42:08,040
Yours, David.

662
00:42:10,720 --> 00:42:12,320
David, why not tell her the truth?

663
00:42:12,320 --> 00:42:13,800
It is the truth.

664
00:42:13,800 --> 00:42:15,360
About your eyes, I mean.

665
00:42:15,360 --> 00:42:17,120
Why not let her decide when she knows?

666
00:42:17,120 --> 00:42:18,560
Will you please send that letter?

667
00:42:18,560 --> 00:42:20,960
- Look, David... 
- Please!

668
00:42:20,960 --> 00:42:22,920
All right, David.

669
00:42:24,320 --> 00:42:26,240
Ted, it's it! It's it!

670
00:42:26,240 --> 00:42:28,680
- It's it! 
- Brought it from Littlewoods?

671
00:42:28,680 --> 00:42:30,600
Wonderful news, man, wonderful.

672
00:42:30,600 --> 00:42:33,320
It's Dillith. There's a baby coming.

673
00:42:33,320 --> 00:42:36,800
Good old Di! I reckon that's the best Christmas present you ever had.

674
00:42:36,800 --> 00:42:41,600
I can see her now, the way she smiles with her eyes.

675
00:42:41,600 --> 00:42:43,520
Aye, indeed. It's lovely to...

676
00:42:43,520 --> 00:42:44,960
How do I look for a godfather?

677
00:42:44,960 --> 00:42:46,880
Ah, yes! That's it, man.

678
00:42:46,880 --> 00:42:49,200
You and Flo. It goes without saying.

679
00:42:49,200 --> 00:42:50,720
And what's the matter?

680
00:42:50,720 --> 00:42:53,160
Got the same chit from the income tax as me, old boy?

681
00:42:53,160 --> 00:42:55,320
Well, don't worry. They can't put us in jag.

682
00:42:55,320 --> 00:42:57,000
We've had it.

683
00:43:25,800 --> 00:43:28,680
What wouldn't I give to see Queen's Park play Rangers this year.

684
00:43:28,680 --> 00:43:31,160
Never mind, padre. They'll be playing over here one day.

685
00:43:31,160 --> 00:43:33,360
'All British prisoners will parade at once.'

686
00:43:33,360 --> 00:43:37,280
- Hello! What's cooking? 
- Forster's on the warpath. They're searching the camp.

687
00:43:37,280 --> 00:43:38,720
Forster again.

688
00:43:38,720 --> 00:43:40,640
'Achtung! Achtung!

689
00:43:40,640 --> 00:43:43,000
'All British prisoners will parade at once.'

690
00:43:43,000 --> 00:43:45,400
Raus, raus!

691
00:43:52,640 --> 00:43:54,080
'Achtung! Achtung!

692
00:43:54,080 --> 00:43:56,480
'All British prisoners will parade at once.'

693
00:43:56,480 --> 00:43:59,840
HE SPEAKS GERMAN

694
00:44:07,120 --> 00:44:10,040
Parade! Halt.

695
00:44:14,240 --> 00:44:17,320
Gentlemen, we have discovered your tunnel.

696
00:44:17,320 --> 00:44:20,000
Since you have thus abused the amenities accorded you,

697
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:24,240
and pending reconsideration of the camp's security measures,

698
00:44:24,240 --> 00:44:28,160
all these amenities will be removed until further notice.

699
00:44:28,160 --> 00:44:32,560
I've given instructions, therefore, to confiscate all books,

700
00:44:32,560 --> 00:44:37,760
writing material, music, all tables and chairs,

701
00:44:37,760 --> 00:44:40,680
bedding, mirrors, knives, and shaving equipment.

702
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:46,440
You may dismiss the parade.

703
00:44:47,840 --> 00:44:50,280
Parade! Dismissed.

704
00:44:57,400 --> 00:44:59,360
I shall have to grow a beard after all.

705
00:44:59,360 --> 00:45:01,760
I don't know whether to have a two-pronged affair

706
00:45:01,760 --> 00:45:04,960
- or a natty little imperial. 
- Wonder how long they'll keep it up.

707
00:45:04,960 --> 00:45:06,560
Not more than a month, I should think.

708
00:45:06,560 --> 00:45:09,480
- I'll keep on nagging the commandant. 
- Good afternoon, gentlemen.

709
00:45:10,880 --> 00:45:12,320
Good afternoon.

710
00:45:12,320 --> 00:45:15,200
I hope this slight setback won't prevent you from trying again.

711
00:45:15,200 --> 00:45:17,640
But I must add,

712
00:45:17,640 --> 00:45:20,000
a moat will be dug around the whole perimeter,

713
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:22,920
which, as you know, makes tunnelling impossible.

714
00:45:25,800 --> 00:45:30,080
Captain Mitchell, who speaks such excellent German...

715
00:45:30,080 --> 00:45:32,920
THEY CONVERSE IN GERMAN

716
00:45:47,720 --> 00:45:50,120
What's he want this time?

717
00:45:50,120 --> 00:45:52,640
Wants to know why I haven't written a single letter home.

718
00:45:52,640 --> 00:45:55,880
Why should you? Mitchell may have had nobody particular to write to.

719
00:45:55,880 --> 00:45:58,400
But he had. This came today.

720
00:45:58,400 --> 00:46:00,360
It's from his wife.

721
00:46:01,760 --> 00:46:04,200
You must answer, or she'll make enquiries.

722
00:46:04,200 --> 00:46:05,600
That'll be fatal.

723
00:46:05,600 --> 00:46:07,040
Seems a pretty cruel fraud.

724
00:46:07,040 --> 00:46:09,920
You're wearing a dead man's shoes. You've got to get used to them.

725
00:46:09,920 --> 00:46:12,320
My handwriting. She'd know it wasn't her husband.

726
00:46:12,320 --> 00:46:13,760
Yes, takes a bit of figuring out.

727
00:46:13,760 --> 00:46:17,640
Alibi for using your left hand. That's what you need.

728
00:46:22,400 --> 00:46:23,880
I can't see much point in this,

729
00:46:23,880 --> 00:46:26,000
now the blighters have taken away the football.

730
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:27,720
Well, anyway, it's good exercise.

731
00:46:27,720 --> 00:46:31,040
Think so? I suppose next week they'll give us back the football

732
00:46:31,040 --> 00:46:32,960
and take away the goalposts.

733
00:46:32,960 --> 00:46:34,720
Come on, it's your turn now.

734
00:46:40,920 --> 00:46:42,120
Ready?

735
00:47:01,760 --> 00:47:03,240
Look out!

736
00:47:08,480 --> 00:47:11,240
- Good morning, Mrs Mitchell. 
- Thank you.

737
00:47:27,680 --> 00:47:30,640
I've mastered the boiler and the power plant.

738
00:47:30,640 --> 00:47:33,920
I won't be defeated by a miserable wireless set.

739
00:47:33,920 --> 00:47:35,360
I've heard from Geoffrey.

740
00:47:35,360 --> 00:47:36,800
Really?

741
00:47:36,800 --> 00:47:38,240
Is he well?

742
00:47:38,240 --> 00:47:39,800
I don't know what to make of it.

743
00:47:39,800 --> 00:47:41,280
He seems to have changed.

744
00:47:41,280 --> 00:47:46,280
Good. Any change in Geoffrey could only be for the better.

745
00:47:46,280 --> 00:47:49,600
Well, the change seems to include his handwriting.

746
00:47:49,600 --> 00:47:51,920
Hurt his hand. He's using his left.

747
00:47:54,600 --> 00:47:56,520
Listen to this.

748
00:47:56,520 --> 00:48:00,520
"It is a world cut off completely from the real world.

749
00:48:00,520 --> 00:48:03,200
"Time stands still here.

750
00:48:03,200 --> 00:48:06,920
"The future is remote. The present empty.

751
00:48:06,920 --> 00:48:11,680
"Even the past begins to seem unreal.

752
00:48:11,680 --> 00:48:15,040
"But a man must have something to hold onto.

753
00:48:15,040 --> 00:48:19,200
"He must forge lengths to keep him sane.

754
00:48:20,640 --> 00:48:22,760
"Will you write to me again, Celia,

755
00:48:22,760 --> 00:48:25,560
"as though I were a stranger?

756
00:48:25,560 --> 00:48:29,680
"Somebody who knows nothing of your life and your home.

757
00:48:31,840 --> 00:48:34,200
"Even of yourself."

758
00:48:34,200 --> 00:48:37,680
Changed?! Why, he's even learned to write grammatically.

759
00:48:39,560 --> 00:48:42,000
Write to him as though he were a stranger...

760
00:48:47,320 --> 00:48:49,560
KNOCKING

761
00:48:59,200 --> 00:49:00,640
Robert!

762
00:49:00,640 --> 00:49:02,120
Come back to be briefed.

763
00:49:02,120 --> 00:49:03,480
Sort of a hush-hush job.

764
00:49:03,480 --> 00:49:05,800
Thought you wouldn't mind if I just called in

765
00:49:05,800 --> 00:49:07,840
to say hail and farewell.

766
00:49:07,840 --> 00:49:10,240
Of course not. Come in.

767
00:49:10,240 --> 00:49:12,520
You look ill, Carol.

768
00:49:12,520 --> 00:49:14,840
I'm all right.

769
00:49:14,840 --> 00:49:17,840
I ran into Beryl in an odd sort of mood.

770
00:49:17,840 --> 00:49:20,120
- I gather she isn't living with you any longer. 
- No.

771
00:49:20,120 --> 00:49:23,080
No, she left soon after you went away.

772
00:49:23,080 --> 00:49:24,760
Heard from Stephen yet?

773
00:49:24,760 --> 00:49:26,680
Oh, yes, I've heard from Stephen.

774
00:49:26,680 --> 00:49:30,040
- What's he say? 
- That our marriage is all washed up.

775
00:49:30,040 --> 00:49:31,520
What?!

776
00:49:31,520 --> 00:49:34,760
He got a letter accusing me of having an affair with you.

777
00:49:34,760 --> 00:49:39,160
Carol, I... But who?

778
00:49:39,160 --> 00:49:41,280
Beryl.

779
00:49:41,280 --> 00:49:44,000
Ahh... I see.

780
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:45,840
And he actually believed it?

781
00:49:45,840 --> 00:49:47,360
Yes.

782
00:49:47,360 --> 00:49:50,040
I'll write back myself and tell him the whole thing's

783
00:49:50,040 --> 00:49:51,520
a deliberate, malicious lie.

784
00:49:51,520 --> 00:49:52,960
What for?

785
00:49:52,960 --> 00:49:56,520
What for?! You don't want Stephen to go on thinking this, do you?

786
00:49:56,520 --> 00:49:58,520
I don't care what he thinks now.

787
00:49:58,520 --> 00:50:00,640
Carol, you mustn't take it like that.

788
00:50:00,640 --> 00:50:02,120
Stephen's a prisoner of war.

789
00:50:02,120 --> 00:50:05,560
If you were in his place, would you pay attention to a poison pen letter?

790
00:50:05,560 --> 00:50:07,560
I don't know.

791
00:50:10,040 --> 00:50:11,840
I'd never been in love before.

792
00:50:14,480 --> 00:50:20,160
I thought being in love meant that you trusted each other completely.

793
00:50:20,160 --> 00:50:24,040
All the things he said,

794
00:50:24,040 --> 00:50:26,800
I believed every word.

795
00:50:26,800 --> 00:50:29,240
Killed my love for him.

796
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:36,600
Caroline, my darling, I can't bear to see you cry.

797
00:50:45,160 --> 00:50:48,520
Don't forget to drop us a line, dear, if there's anything you want.

798
00:50:48,520 --> 00:50:50,080
I've tried to get used to it,

799
00:50:50,080 --> 00:50:51,600
but I still can't believe it.

800
00:50:51,600 --> 00:50:53,000
We were so much in love.

801
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:56,160
- Ah, it's a mystery to me. 
- He has a right to change his mind, I suppose.

802
00:50:56,160 --> 00:50:59,800
Could it be that he doesn't think it's fair to make Elspeth wait on and on?

803
00:50:59,800 --> 00:51:01,480
Do you think it might be that?

804
00:51:01,480 --> 00:51:03,120
No. I don't think David's the kind

805
00:51:03,120 --> 00:51:05,920
to make that sort of sacrifice for that sort of reason.

806
00:51:07,160 --> 00:51:10,120
- Goodbye, my darling. 
- Goodbye. 
- Goodbye.

807
00:51:13,320 --> 00:51:16,640
'The photograph I'm sending makes me look absurdly young,

808
00:51:16,640 --> 00:51:19,280
'but I'm no longer young.

809
00:51:19,280 --> 00:51:22,400
'The one of Janet, that funny expression's only shyness,

810
00:51:22,400 --> 00:51:23,680
'not a stomach ache.

811
00:51:23,680 --> 00:51:26,280
'I can see her now through the window

812
00:51:26,280 --> 00:51:29,320
'telling her grandpapa how to plant tomatoes.

813
00:51:29,320 --> 00:51:30,960
'I'm worried about her teeth.

814
00:51:30,960 --> 00:51:34,680
'Father thinks she should wear one of those wire things.

815
00:51:34,680 --> 00:51:39,040
'And that hulking boy is Desmond. Nine years old yesterday.

816
00:51:39,040 --> 00:51:41,920
'The village is livelier than it's ever been.

817
00:51:41,920 --> 00:51:44,000
'We have a large contingent of evacuees

818
00:51:44,000 --> 00:51:46,920
'and a lot of other visitors that come and go.

819
00:51:46,920 --> 00:51:49,600
'Everything's changed and yet nothing's changed.

820
00:51:49,600 --> 00:51:51,960
'There's the whistle of the 4:35.

821
00:51:51,960 --> 00:51:54,040
'Half an hour late as usual.

822
00:51:54,040 --> 00:51:57,120
'Mrs Trusket still serves her homemade toffee.

823
00:51:57,120 --> 00:52:00,680
'Where she manages to get the sugar from, I can't imagine.

824
00:52:00,680 --> 00:52:03,080
'And there's still cricket on Saturday afternoon.'

825
00:52:47,360 --> 00:52:50,160
Oh, what a kick in the pants that turned out to be.

826
00:52:50,160 --> 00:52:52,320
Five times more officers than other ranks

827
00:52:52,320 --> 00:52:54,360
and they have to knock the stuffing out of us.

828
00:52:54,360 --> 00:52:56,640
It was a mistake having long-on too close to the wire.

829
00:52:56,640 --> 00:52:58,720
If he has to run back to take a catch, he's had it.

830
00:52:58,720 --> 00:53:01,440
Do you know what the Jerries want for a new ball? 500 cigarettes.

831
00:53:01,440 --> 00:53:05,280
- Sheer blackmail. 
- Oh, I think it's worth it if this marvellous weather continues.

832
00:53:05,280 --> 00:53:08,360
I wonder if they've been having an early spring at home.

833
00:53:08,360 --> 00:53:11,040
"The apple trees are in full blossom already,

834
00:53:11,040 --> 00:53:16,000
"making the orchard look like a sheet of fleecy snow.

835
00:53:16,000 --> 00:53:18,680
"And 10-Acre Meadow is all white, too.

836
00:53:18,680 --> 00:53:20,000
"Because this year,

837
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:23,920
"that's where the ewes are pastured with their lambs.

838
00:53:23,920 --> 00:53:27,040
"Soon the garden will be filled with the scent

839
00:53:27,040 --> 00:53:29,000
"and colour of the May.

840
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:31,480
"And beyond the river,

841
00:53:31,480 --> 00:53:35,560
"you can see the first vivid green of the larches

842
00:53:35,560 --> 00:53:38,040
"in the bluebell wood."

843
00:53:50,200 --> 00:53:52,040
- Ted? 
- Yeah?

844
00:53:52,040 --> 00:53:53,920
Remember that redhead I told you about?

845
00:53:53,920 --> 00:53:56,200
Let's see, is that your own true dream girl lovey pie

846
00:53:56,200 --> 00:53:58,080
or cheerio, toots?

847
00:53:58,080 --> 00:53:59,400
No! It's my steady.

848
00:53:59,400 --> 00:54:01,800
She says the works manager's fallen for her.

849
00:54:01,800 --> 00:54:03,120
Says he's a key man.

850
00:54:03,120 --> 00:54:05,640
Sounds like one of them backdoor key men to me.

851
00:54:05,640 --> 00:54:07,040
You and your pin-up girls.

852
00:54:07,040 --> 00:54:09,920
My pinup's Tessie O'Shea, with a rawlplug.

853
00:54:09,920 --> 00:54:12,320
- Yeah, but in my experience... 
- Your experience?

854
00:54:12,320 --> 00:54:14,720
Cor blimey, one sniff of a barmaid's apron,

855
00:54:14,720 --> 00:54:16,480
and you'd be on your knees, sonny boy.

856
00:54:16,480 --> 00:54:19,720
That's all you know. Teach you a thing or two.

857
00:54:21,120 --> 00:54:24,160
What's the matter, Ted? Bad news?

858
00:54:24,160 --> 00:54:25,600
Ted?

859
00:54:27,600 --> 00:54:29,360
Blimey, I never saw that one.

860
00:54:29,360 --> 00:54:31,720
Hey, my old woman's gone on the buses.

861
00:54:31,720 --> 00:54:35,200
- Oh, you'll be walking the kids when you get home. 
- If we get home.

862
00:54:35,200 --> 00:54:38,320
It's a firm stand I'm going to take.

863
00:54:38,320 --> 00:54:40,560
The rest of them you can eat,

864
00:54:40,560 --> 00:54:42,320
but not Lili Marleen.

865
00:54:42,320 --> 00:54:46,240
She's got such a trusting look in her eye.

866
00:54:46,240 --> 00:54:51,400
Besides, next winter I shall use her as a hot water bottle.

867
00:54:51,400 --> 00:54:53,680
I've had a letter, Dai.

868
00:54:53,680 --> 00:54:57,440
Amazing. Perhaps there's one for me

869
00:54:57,440 --> 00:54:58,920
with news of the baby.

870
00:54:58,920 --> 00:55:00,960
No letter for you.

871
00:55:00,960 --> 00:55:02,760
There is news.

872
00:55:02,760 --> 00:55:04,600
Flo's all right?

873
00:55:04,600 --> 00:55:06,440
Not Ann-Marie?

874
00:55:06,440 --> 00:55:08,960
She's OK. Letter's from her.

875
00:55:10,760 --> 00:55:14,800
"It's a baby girl. She's doing nice.

876
00:55:14,800 --> 00:55:17,640
"Dillith..."

877
00:55:19,160 --> 00:55:21,960
You'll have it sooner or later.

878
00:55:21,960 --> 00:55:26,120
Seems that doctor warned her about it being dangerous,

879
00:55:26,120 --> 00:55:29,280
because of her age.

880
00:55:29,280 --> 00:55:31,600
She wouldn't be put off.

881
00:55:31,600 --> 00:55:34,600
Flo was with her at the end.

882
00:55:34,600 --> 00:55:37,120
It was all over quite quick.

883
00:55:37,120 --> 00:55:41,120
Flo's going to look after the baby until you get back.

884
00:55:59,200 --> 00:56:00,480
The play's the thing.

885
00:56:00,480 --> 00:56:03,840
Wherein I'll catch the conscience of the king.

886
00:56:03,840 --> 00:56:05,640
Well, what happens in the end?

887
00:56:05,640 --> 00:56:08,120
Do they bump the dirty old basket off?

888
00:56:08,120 --> 00:56:10,280
Well, there's a sort of all-round massacre,

889
00:56:10,280 --> 00:56:11,840
and Hamlet gets killed himself.

890
00:56:11,840 --> 00:56:14,880
First class gangster stuff. The old boy certainly knew his onion.

891
00:56:14,880 --> 00:56:16,680
You wait till we get to Richard III.

892
00:56:16,680 --> 00:56:18,720
There's a murder on practically every page.

893
00:56:18,720 --> 00:56:21,120
You're getting pretty hot at this Braille business.

894
00:56:21,120 --> 00:56:24,640
Och, it's easy. But I'm still terrible clumsy with my hands.

895
00:56:24,640 --> 00:56:28,400
Oh, I don't know about that. That tobacco pouch you made was smashing.

896
00:56:28,400 --> 00:56:30,560
I've got sort of used to it now.

897
00:56:30,560 --> 00:56:32,480
And, well, you've all been so...

898
00:56:32,480 --> 00:56:35,520
You get on with your reading. I want to know what happens next.

899
00:56:35,520 --> 00:56:37,000
Right.

900
00:56:38,400 --> 00:56:41,480
'Celia, your letter has arrived with the photographs.

901
00:56:41,480 --> 00:56:44,520
'They're in front of me as I write.

902
00:56:44,520 --> 00:56:46,880
'You ask me to describe our life here

903
00:56:46,880 --> 00:56:50,240
'so that you may picture it in your imagination.

904
00:56:50,240 --> 00:56:54,120
'From where I sit, I can hear the sound of a piano.

905
00:56:54,120 --> 00:56:56,800
'It is my friend Stephen Harley.

906
00:56:56,800 --> 00:56:59,720
'I wish you could hear this music,

907
00:56:59,720 --> 00:57:01,760
'for it describes our life here

908
00:57:01,760 --> 00:57:04,520
'better than I could ever do with words.

909
00:57:04,520 --> 00:57:07,520
'It tells of men emerging from the twilight.

910
00:57:07,520 --> 00:57:10,240
'Turning their faces inwards from the wire.

911
00:57:10,240 --> 00:57:14,160
'Creating in miniature a world of their own.

912
00:57:16,240 --> 00:57:19,040
'It tells of men who have come to terms with the present

913
00:57:19,040 --> 00:57:22,560
'and find it far from empty.

914
00:57:22,560 --> 00:57:26,360
'Men who no longer lie down to fate but face it.

915
00:57:27,920 --> 00:57:30,120
'And find their own ways of beating it.'

916
00:57:49,240 --> 00:57:51,760
THEY SING HYMN

917
00:58:02,520 --> 00:58:04,880
GENTLE CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYS

918
00:58:21,120 --> 00:58:23,080
RAUCOUS LAUGHTER

919
00:58:26,880 --> 00:58:29,040
HOOTING AND WOLF-WHISTLES

920
00:58:39,440 --> 00:58:43,400
'All this goes to make up the picture of our life here,

921
00:58:43,400 --> 00:58:45,720
'made bearable only by the letters and parcels

922
00:58:45,720 --> 00:58:46,760
'we receive from home.

923
00:58:46,760 --> 00:58:51,240
'They keep our bodies and our faith alive.

924
00:58:51,240 --> 00:58:53,240
'And that is true not only of us

925
00:58:53,240 --> 00:58:56,240
'here in our little wired enclosed cinder patch,

926
00:58:56,240 --> 00:58:59,440
'but also of the scores of other camps throughout Germany.

927
00:58:59,440 --> 00:59:02,720
'Great sprawling towns of 20,000 men

928
00:59:02,720 --> 00:59:06,720
'or hamlets of a few hundred, each a little piece of England.'

929
00:59:11,680 --> 00:59:15,560
'The months pass and my thoughts are constantly of you, Celia.

930
00:59:15,560 --> 00:59:19,960
'Summer gives place to autumn, autumn to winter.

931
00:59:19,960 --> 00:59:22,200
'Another Christmas come and gone.

932
00:59:22,200 --> 00:59:24,480
'Another batch of prisoners to swell our numbers.

933
00:59:24,480 --> 00:59:26,760
'They don't make the housing problem any easier.

934
00:59:26,760 --> 00:59:30,600
'But they bring us eagerly awaited news of the outside world.

935
00:59:30,600 --> 00:59:32,520
'A little while ago there was a rumour

936
00:59:32,520 --> 00:59:34,400
'that some of us were to be repatriated.

937
00:59:34,400 --> 00:59:37,680
'I allowed myself to dream that these letters of ours

938
00:59:37,680 --> 00:59:38,920
'could come to life.

939
00:59:38,920 --> 00:59:42,320
'I could see with my own eyes your home, the children,

940
00:59:42,320 --> 00:59:44,160
'yourself.

941
00:59:44,160 --> 00:59:46,560
'But the commission never came.

942
00:59:46,560 --> 00:59:48,000
'Were we forgotten?

943
00:59:48,000 --> 00:59:51,240
'Or was it just one more reprisal?'

944
00:59:51,240 --> 00:59:53,840
Being they are prisoners,

945
00:59:53,840 --> 00:59:56,240
this practice must come to rest.

946
00:59:56,240 --> 00:59:59,160
Orders.

947
00:59:59,160 --> 01:00:02,880
Finally, the recent operations at Dieppe,

948
01:00:02,880 --> 01:00:08,800
as a reprisal for such an unwarranted action,

949
01:00:08,800 --> 01:00:14,320
all British prisoners of war of cellblock 27

950
01:00:14,320 --> 01:00:17,880
will, until further notice, remain manacled

951
01:00:17,880 --> 01:00:20,760
from dawn until dusk.

952
01:00:25,280 --> 01:00:28,240
You may dismiss the parade.

953
01:00:28,240 --> 01:00:30,520
HE SHOUTS ORDERS

954
01:00:57,000 --> 01:00:58,240
Cigarette?

955
01:00:58,240 --> 01:01:00,680
Thanks.

956
01:01:00,680 --> 01:01:03,160
It's easy. Sardine key.

957
01:01:03,160 --> 01:01:04,960
Turn to the right.

958
01:01:04,960 --> 01:01:06,720
Turn to the left.

959
01:01:06,720 --> 01:01:08,040
Bob's your uncle.

960
01:01:08,040 --> 01:01:10,000
All part of the Red Cross service.

961
01:01:10,000 --> 01:01:11,720
THEY LAUGH

962
01:01:12,840 --> 01:01:15,720
'Our third winter is approaching,

963
01:01:15,720 --> 01:01:18,080
'bringing with it a new enemy.

964
01:01:18,080 --> 01:01:21,960
'It's not the duration but the indefiniteness.

965
01:01:21,960 --> 01:01:24,640
'For if a man knew the length of his sentence,

966
01:01:24,640 --> 01:01:27,040
'he could plan accordingly.

967
01:01:27,040 --> 01:01:29,280
'Afterwards in our memories,

968
01:01:29,280 --> 01:01:31,520
'we shall relive only the sunny days

969
01:01:31,520 --> 01:01:32,960
'or pleasant scenes,

970
01:01:32,960 --> 01:01:35,800
'the freedom of mind and the comradeship.

971
01:01:35,800 --> 01:01:38,960
'We shall forget the wet days, the wet weeks.

972
01:01:38,960 --> 01:01:41,640
'Those days when it seemed an effort to do nothing

973
01:01:41,640 --> 01:01:44,760
'and our bunks were the only release.

974
01:01:44,760 --> 01:01:47,040
'Deep down in the hearts of all of us,

975
01:01:47,040 --> 01:01:49,160
'there dwells a lonely ache,

976
01:01:49,160 --> 01:01:52,440
'a desperate yearning for those we love

977
01:01:52,440 --> 01:01:56,680
'and a fear, fear of becoming forgotten men.

978
01:01:58,720 --> 01:02:00,640
'Write to me again soon, Celia.

979
01:02:00,640 --> 01:02:02,880
'You could never know how great the comfort is

980
01:02:02,880 --> 01:02:04,760
'that your letters bring to me.

981
01:02:04,760 --> 01:02:06,240
'They're more than comfort.

982
01:02:06,240 --> 01:02:10,560
'They give me strength and hope and happiness.

983
01:02:10,560 --> 01:02:13,160
'You will never know how much they mean to me.'

984
01:02:14,880 --> 01:02:18,720
'Oh, my dear, I am so terribly moved by the way you write.

985
01:02:18,720 --> 01:02:24,480
'Is it too late to recapture the happiness of our first years together?'

986
01:02:27,360 --> 01:02:31,360
'I have no place in your past or your future, Celia.

987
01:02:31,360 --> 01:02:33,440
'You must think of your husband as dead.

988
01:02:33,440 --> 01:02:35,520
'This is goodbye.'

989
01:02:35,520 --> 01:02:39,760
'I understand. Don't be afraid.

990
01:02:39,760 --> 01:02:42,400
'I'll help you back.

991
01:02:42,400 --> 01:02:44,960
'I'll give you back your strength,

992
01:02:44,960 --> 01:02:49,240
'the strength you've given to me writing to me through these dark years.

993
01:02:51,040 --> 01:02:53,120
'I'll wait for you.'

994
01:03:09,920 --> 01:03:12,640
DISTANT DRONE OF PLANES

995
01:03:18,360 --> 01:03:20,040
PLANES APPROACH

996
01:03:36,520 --> 01:03:38,200
Fortresses.

997
01:03:38,200 --> 01:03:40,640
They'll soon be able to see the Channel.

998
01:03:40,640 --> 01:03:43,920
They'll be home in time for tea.

999
01:03:58,320 --> 01:04:01,080
That's exactly £157 you owe me.

1000
01:04:01,080 --> 01:04:03,400
Cut you through the pack. Double or quits.

1001
01:04:03,400 --> 01:04:06,280
Not on your life. I've got my old age to think of.

1002
01:04:06,280 --> 01:04:07,680
Bloodsucker.

1003
01:04:07,680 --> 01:04:10,760
Oh, well, bang goes my gratuity.

1004
01:04:10,760 --> 01:04:13,000
Cheap enough to pass the time.

1005
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:15,720
Funny how much you learn about time when you're killing it.

1006
01:04:15,720 --> 01:04:17,400
Such as what?

1007
01:04:17,400 --> 01:04:21,000
I've got a theory that everything that counts is done by busy people.

1008
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:24,560
When you've got too little time, it's extraordinary what you can do with it.

1009
01:04:24,560 --> 01:04:26,600
And when you've got all the time in the world,

1010
01:04:26,600 --> 01:04:28,880
like us, you don't do a damn thing.

1011
01:04:28,880 --> 01:04:31,520
I say, you're becoming quite a philosopher in your old age.

1012
01:04:31,520 --> 01:04:34,360
Why not? The war hasn't exactly chosen us to be heroes.

1013
01:04:34,360 --> 01:04:36,920
I know exactly what I'm going to do with my time right now.

1014
01:04:36,920 --> 01:04:38,680
I'm going to climb into my bunk

1015
01:04:38,680 --> 01:04:40,920
and do absolutely nothing till supper.

1016
01:04:40,920 --> 01:04:46,280
They're talking about Teran for the derby this year.

1017
01:04:46,280 --> 01:04:49,160
It'll be the fourth derby I've missed.

1018
01:04:49,160 --> 01:04:52,440
Four derbies. That's a hell of a lot of time.

1019
01:04:52,440 --> 01:04:56,360
With nothing up or down on the book to show for it.

1020
01:05:03,720 --> 01:05:06,600
Planting leeks again this year, Dai?

1021
01:05:06,600 --> 01:05:09,040
I was thinking of trying some asparagus.

1022
01:05:09,040 --> 01:05:11,920
Asparagus? That takes seven years, cock.

1023
01:05:11,920 --> 01:05:13,200
Aye.

1024
01:05:13,200 --> 01:05:15,280
I don't give it more than another year myself.

1025
01:05:15,280 --> 01:05:17,720
Another year?

1026
01:05:17,720 --> 01:05:20,520
Gwyneth will be four.

1027
01:05:20,520 --> 01:05:22,960
Flo's hair has gone all white, she says.

1028
01:05:22,960 --> 01:05:24,880
Everything's changing.

1029
01:05:24,880 --> 01:05:26,920
Do you think we'll be able to pick it up?

1030
01:05:26,920 --> 01:05:28,680
The business and everything?

1031
01:05:28,680 --> 01:05:31,880
Search me. We're not as young as we were, Dai.

1032
01:05:31,880 --> 01:05:35,400
No, Ted, we're not as young as we were.

1033
01:05:38,520 --> 01:05:39,800
Surely they'll invade soon.

1034
01:05:39,800 --> 01:05:42,040
Yeah, that's what you said last year.

1035
01:05:42,040 --> 01:05:43,440
And the year before.

1036
01:05:43,440 --> 01:05:45,040
What's there, mate, holiday list?

1037
01:05:45,040 --> 01:05:48,240
Yeah, it's got you down for August, 1949.

1038
01:05:48,240 --> 01:05:51,080
I wrote that for Caroline.

1039
01:05:51,080 --> 01:05:54,960
Somehow it expressed what I felt when I first met her.

1040
01:05:54,960 --> 01:05:56,720
It was after a concert.

1041
01:05:56,720 --> 01:05:58,160
There weren't any taxis.

1042
01:05:58,160 --> 01:06:00,440
We walked back across the park.

1043
01:06:00,440 --> 01:06:02,120
After a bit, it began to rain.

1044
01:06:02,120 --> 01:06:05,480
I put my coat over her shoulders.

1045
01:06:05,480 --> 01:06:07,840
You're still in love with her, aren't you?

1046
01:06:07,840 --> 01:06:10,800
I've tried to shut her out of my thoughts completely.

1047
01:06:10,800 --> 01:06:15,200
But I can't. I long for her all the time.

1048
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:18,760
I'm a bigger fool than you are.

1049
01:06:18,760 --> 01:06:22,440
Falling in love with a photograph. A dream.

1050
01:06:23,920 --> 01:06:26,960
And a home in a strange land.

1051
01:06:26,960 --> 01:06:28,720
Achtung!

1052
01:06:28,720 --> 01:06:30,640
Oh, carry on.

1053
01:06:30,640 --> 01:06:32,840
Good afternoon, gentlemen.

1054
01:06:32,840 --> 01:06:34,120
Oh, please, do carry on.

1055
01:06:34,120 --> 01:06:36,720
Each time I visit this camp,

1056
01:06:36,720 --> 01:06:38,800
I'm intrigued as to where we met before.

1057
01:06:38,800 --> 01:06:40,680
But now I think I know the answer.

1058
01:06:40,680 --> 01:06:44,080
Your name wasn't always Geoffrey Mitchell.

1059
01:06:44,080 --> 01:06:46,480
Your identification photograph is being sent

1060
01:06:46,480 --> 01:06:49,320
to Gestapo headquarters in Berlin.

1061
01:06:49,320 --> 01:06:52,280
They have a large collection of photographs there.

1062
01:06:52,280 --> 01:06:55,800
It will be interesting to make comparisons.

1063
01:06:59,120 --> 01:07:00,720
I suppose it had to come.

1064
01:07:00,720 --> 01:07:03,160
They always catch up with you in the end.

1065
01:07:03,160 --> 01:07:05,720
Repatriation, fellas! Repatriation!

1066
01:07:05,720 --> 01:07:07,400
THEY ALL SCOFF

1067
01:07:07,400 --> 01:07:10,160
Great news, gentlemen, great news! Repatriation!

1068
01:07:10,160 --> 01:07:12,920
And this time it's the real McCoy.

1069
01:07:12,920 --> 01:07:15,160
The thing that makes me mouth water, real live girls.

1070
01:07:15,160 --> 01:07:17,560
- All lining up waiting for me. 
- Girls, what are they?

1071
01:07:17,560 --> 01:07:20,720
Bipeds, old boy, furnished with two of practically everything!

1072
01:07:20,720 --> 01:07:23,520
A mixed German and Swiss medical commission

1073
01:07:23,520 --> 01:07:26,800
will examine all those whose names are down for repatriation.

1074
01:07:26,800 --> 01:07:30,320
Apparently it's a rush job, so anybody who gets his ticket

1075
01:07:30,320 --> 01:07:31,800
will leave in a week's time.

1076
01:07:31,800 --> 01:07:34,640
MEN CHEER So you've got a chance.

1077
01:07:34,640 --> 01:07:36,280
Yes.

1078
01:07:36,280 --> 01:07:39,280
But we must have positive evidence to justify repatriation.

1079
01:07:39,280 --> 01:07:40,560
Of course.

1080
01:07:40,560 --> 01:07:42,640
Ah. Anything else, Corporal?

1081
01:07:42,640 --> 01:07:44,560
Well, sir, every time I breathe,

1082
01:07:44,560 --> 01:07:47,040
I can feel me liver knocking up against me kidneys.

1083
01:07:47,040 --> 01:07:49,560
- Come here. 
- Yes, sir.

1084
01:07:49,560 --> 01:07:50,800
Cough, please.

1085
01:07:50,800 --> 01:07:53,600
Cough? Blimey, do you want me to bring up my appendix?

1086
01:07:55,280 --> 01:07:56,760
Ja.

1087
01:08:01,280 --> 01:08:02,640
You have passed.

1088
01:08:02,640 --> 01:08:03,920
Thank you, sir.

1089
01:08:03,920 --> 01:08:04,960
Matthews.

1090
01:08:04,960 --> 01:08:06,880
I wonder if you'll get through.

1091
01:08:06,880 --> 01:08:09,200
Hello, Evans. You'll soon be seeing your youngster.

1092
01:08:09,200 --> 01:08:13,360
Yes, indeed. I'm sorry to hear about you and Captain Grayson, sir.

1093
01:08:13,360 --> 01:08:15,400
Oh, well, the flat racing season's over.

1094
01:08:15,400 --> 01:08:18,320
That Swiss fellow had the nerve to congratulate me on my fitness.

1095
01:08:18,320 --> 01:08:19,760
Ha ha! Well?

1096
01:08:19,760 --> 01:08:21,480
- I got my ticket, all right. 
- Fine.

1097
01:08:21,480 --> 01:08:23,120
You have passed.

1098
01:08:23,120 --> 01:08:25,120
Suits me, sir.

1099
01:08:27,600 --> 01:08:29,840
Captain Mitchell.

1100
01:08:35,320 --> 01:08:36,400
Ah.

1101
01:08:36,400 --> 01:08:39,160
You need not strip, Captain Mitchell.

1102
01:08:39,160 --> 01:08:40,720
I regret your case is deferred

1103
01:08:40,720 --> 01:08:44,280
until the next board in six months' time.

1104
01:08:48,240 --> 01:08:49,680
Morris.

1105
01:08:49,680 --> 01:08:53,840
And once it's discovered he's not Mitchell, he's sunk. We've got to do something for him.

1106
01:08:53,840 --> 01:08:55,080
Yes, but what?

1107
01:08:55,080 --> 01:08:58,160
- Excuse me, sir. Can we put up a scheme to you? 
- Sure. Sit down.

1108
01:08:58,160 --> 01:09:00,880
- What's it all about? 
- We know the spot Captain Mitchell's in.

1109
01:09:00,880 --> 01:09:04,400
- We thought we'd fix a stunt to get him out of here. 
- What's the scheme?

1110
01:09:04,400 --> 01:09:07,160
There's a list for repatriation in the commandant's office.

1111
01:09:07,160 --> 01:09:10,320
- We thought if we could get it, alter the names... 
- Stage a break-in, sir.

1112
01:09:10,320 --> 01:09:12,560
Here, hold on. We aren't professional burglars.

1113
01:09:12,560 --> 01:09:14,960
Well, yes, sir, as a matter of fact... well, I was.

1114
01:09:14,960 --> 01:09:17,960
Were you really? Well, how awfully interesting.

1115
01:09:17,960 --> 01:09:20,280
Commandant's office. Only one wire to cut.

1116
01:09:20,280 --> 01:09:22,360
Yes, but what about the perimeter lights?

1117
01:09:22,360 --> 01:09:26,040
- They put them out when there's an air raid. 
- And they've been as regular as clockwork.

1118
01:09:26,040 --> 01:09:27,600
I believe we've got something!

1119
01:09:27,600 --> 01:09:30,000
- Suppose we do get the list. What then? 
- I can type.

1120
01:09:30,000 --> 01:09:32,440
Scratch out one name and type Mitchell's on instead.

1121
01:09:32,440 --> 01:09:36,200
Just a minute. Don't you see, the chap whose name goes off has to stay behind.

1122
01:09:36,200 --> 01:09:38,480
Well, uh, my name begins with M, sir.

1123
01:09:38,480 --> 01:09:41,320
You'd really give up your ticket home?

1124
01:09:41,320 --> 01:09:42,880
Why not?

1125
01:09:42,880 --> 01:09:45,560
But I thought all the girls were lining up for you to come home?

1126
01:09:45,560 --> 01:09:48,320
Well, so they are. But they'll wait.

1127
01:09:48,320 --> 01:09:49,840
You are a sportsman.

1128
01:09:49,840 --> 01:09:51,440
Gentleman, we'll have a smack at it.

1129
01:09:51,440 --> 01:09:54,440
Now, as I see it, the drill is this...

1130
01:09:57,440 --> 01:10:01,120
DISTANT SINGING

1131
01:10:24,400 --> 01:10:28,240
# My eyes are dim, I cannot see

1132
01:10:28,240 --> 01:10:31,800
# I have not brought my specs with me... #

1133
01:10:31,800 --> 01:10:33,440
Shh, shhh!

1134
01:10:33,440 --> 01:10:36,120
PLANES APPROACH

1135
01:10:38,720 --> 01:10:40,400
Here come the boys. Bang on the dot.

1136
01:10:40,400 --> 01:10:43,000
- What do you mean? 
- Well, just another raid, old boy.

1137
01:10:44,880 --> 01:10:47,440
All right, chaps, light up and sing out.

1138
01:10:47,440 --> 01:10:50,120
THEY CONTINUE SINGING

1139
01:10:59,600 --> 01:11:01,560
Well, they had better start.

1140
01:11:01,560 --> 01:11:04,320
I know. God bless the RAF.

1141
01:11:12,440 --> 01:11:13,680
Here he is.

1142
01:11:13,680 --> 01:11:15,640
Good boy. Look out!

1143
01:12:05,040 --> 01:12:07,120
All clear.

1144
01:12:19,480 --> 01:12:22,080
THEY CHAT IN GERMAN

1145
01:12:27,040 --> 01:12:29,280
THEY LAUGH

1146
01:12:53,480 --> 01:12:55,680
That's the lock you've got to pick.

1147
01:13:01,400 --> 01:13:02,960
Good, there's a typewriter.

1148
01:13:02,960 --> 01:13:04,520
Get down!

1149
01:13:06,160 --> 01:13:08,360
- Type on the floor. 
- OK.

1150
01:13:09,640 --> 01:13:11,440
It's tougher than I thought.

1151
01:13:11,440 --> 01:13:13,040
Let me try.

1152
01:13:17,680 --> 01:13:21,560
- Must be a bit out of practice. 
- I'll say.

1153
01:13:21,560 --> 01:13:24,400
Einrichtung, einrichtung...

1154
01:13:24,400 --> 01:13:26,760
Good, this is it.

1155
01:13:50,720 --> 01:13:53,720
Sing, you so-and-sos, sing!

1156
01:14:00,480 --> 01:14:02,520
- That'll do. 
- Come on.

1157
01:14:27,760 --> 01:14:29,040
- That'll fool 'em. 
- Should do.

1158
01:14:29,040 --> 01:14:32,440
- Let's split up and get back to our own huts. 
- OK, sir.

1159
01:14:42,240 --> 01:14:44,600
DOG GROWLS

1160
01:14:49,320 --> 01:14:51,640
GUNSHOTS

1161
01:14:51,640 --> 01:14:53,960
- What's going on? 
- You're not supposed to know.

1162
01:14:53,960 --> 01:14:56,440
The boys were putting your name on the repatriation list.

1163
01:14:56,440 --> 01:14:58,160
GUNSHOTS

1164
01:15:09,680 --> 01:15:11,360
DOG HOWLS

1165
01:15:17,040 --> 01:15:19,160
GUNFIRE CONTINUES

1166
01:15:32,640 --> 01:15:34,760
MUSIC AND SINGING

1167
01:15:40,560 --> 01:15:43,800
You will all remain here until the other huts have been checked!

1168
01:16:04,200 --> 01:16:05,720
Permission to go home, sir?

1169
01:16:05,720 --> 01:16:09,760
Yes, provided you put a fiver on Teran at the derby for me.

1170
01:16:09,760 --> 01:16:13,040
- It's you that ought to be going home. 
- Oh, don't you believe it.

1171
01:16:13,040 --> 01:16:14,760
I'm a social parasite.

1172
01:16:14,760 --> 01:16:16,800
The sort we're fighting to get rid of.

1173
01:16:16,800 --> 01:16:19,200
That's right. I've got to stay here and exterminate him.

1174
01:16:19,200 --> 01:16:21,400
Go slow with the popsies, old boy.

1175
01:16:21,400 --> 01:16:24,400
Don't forget to save a couple of blondes for your Uncle Jim.

1176
01:16:24,400 --> 01:16:26,840
- That's a promise. 
- Course, I was forgetting.

1177
01:16:26,840 --> 01:16:29,240
You're one of those one-woman blokes, aren't you?

1178
01:16:29,240 --> 01:16:30,760
Yes, that's my trouble.

1179
01:16:30,760 --> 01:16:32,920
Sorry, then. Always putting my foot in it.

1180
01:16:32,920 --> 01:16:35,360
Tell the girls round Hammersmith that I'll be home soon

1181
01:16:35,360 --> 01:16:37,720
and I've got plenty saved up to give them a treat with.

1182
01:16:37,720 --> 01:16:40,040
- Yeah, you bet. 
- I'll keep a job warm for him.

1183
01:16:40,040 --> 01:16:43,240
- Horsfall, Evans, and Mathews. 
- Unlimited.

1184
01:16:45,800 --> 01:16:48,080
Hello, Mathews. Feeling all right?

1185
01:16:48,080 --> 01:16:51,040
Yes, it's all right, sir. I was a sissy passing out like that.

1186
01:16:51,040 --> 01:16:52,880
I can never thank you for what you've done.

1187
01:16:52,880 --> 01:16:56,480
Forget it. Just keep your head down on the parade and Bob's your uncle.

1188
01:16:56,480 --> 01:16:59,080
- Thanks. 
- Don't worry, sir. You'll get through all right.

1189
01:16:59,080 --> 01:17:00,520
We'll be right behind you, sir.

1190
01:17:03,960 --> 01:17:06,680
One other thing. What about the German MO?

1191
01:17:06,680 --> 01:17:07,920
He's certain to be on parade,

1192
01:17:07,920 --> 01:17:10,920
and he's likely to remember that Mitchell's name wasn't on the list.

1193
01:17:10,920 --> 01:17:12,240
I know. I've thought of that.

1194
01:17:12,240 --> 01:17:15,360
I'm going to start up a conversation while they're calling the names.

1195
01:17:15,360 --> 01:17:17,200
He only speaks about a dozen words in English.

1196
01:17:17,200 --> 01:17:18,800
You leave it to me.

1197
01:17:18,800 --> 01:17:20,880
Hello, David, my boy.

1198
01:17:20,880 --> 01:17:24,160
Goodbye and good luck.

1199
01:17:24,160 --> 01:17:27,880
Goodbye, sir, and thank you all.

1200
01:17:27,880 --> 01:17:30,040
See you again before you know where you are.

1201
01:17:30,040 --> 01:17:32,280
- Yes. 
- Come on, David.

1202
01:17:32,280 --> 01:17:34,440
Don't forget. We've got a bridge date tonight.

1203
01:17:34,440 --> 01:17:36,280
Don't forget the cigarettes you owe me.

1204
01:17:36,280 --> 01:17:37,880
Play you double or quits tonight.

1205
01:17:37,880 --> 01:17:39,000
Ambrose.

1206
01:17:40,440 --> 01:17:41,520
Anderson.

1207
01:17:42,960 --> 01:17:44,960
Burns.

1208
01:17:44,960 --> 01:17:48,160
There are a lot of things I'd like to say, but...

1209
01:17:48,160 --> 01:17:49,320
but I can't.

1210
01:17:49,320 --> 01:17:52,200
Go on. Off you go.

1211
01:17:52,200 --> 01:17:54,840
Goodbye. Good luck.

1212
01:17:54,840 --> 01:17:56,960
- So long, old boy. 
- Good luck.

1213
01:17:56,960 --> 01:17:58,840
Keep out of the German MO's eyeline.

1214
01:18:00,080 --> 01:18:01,480
Grant.

1215
01:18:02,680 --> 01:18:03,800
Harley.

1216
01:18:05,160 --> 01:18:06,280
Hunt.

1217
01:18:07,680 --> 01:18:10,040
Horsfall.

1218
01:18:10,040 --> 01:18:11,360
Jackson.

1219
01:18:12,560 --> 01:18:13,880
Jessop.

1220
01:18:15,240 --> 01:18:17,480
How soon do you think the war will end now, Doctor?

1221
01:18:17,480 --> 01:18:19,640
Six months or one year.

1222
01:18:19,640 --> 01:18:21,880
By then, you'll be speaking fluent English.

1223
01:18:21,880 --> 01:18:23,800
You think I've made good progression?

1224
01:18:23,800 --> 01:18:27,640
Oh, terrific. Yes, you Germans certainly have a gift for languages.

1225
01:18:27,640 --> 01:18:30,600
- You think so? 
- Of course. Yes.

1226
01:18:30,600 --> 01:18:34,120
After the war, they might make me headmaster of Oxford University.

1227
01:18:34,120 --> 01:18:35,880
THEY LAUGH

1228
01:18:35,880 --> 01:18:37,080
Mitchell.

1229
01:18:40,720 --> 01:18:42,000
Mitre.

1230
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:44,000
THEY LAUGH

1231
01:18:46,440 --> 01:18:49,040
Achtung. March!

1232
01:18:49,040 --> 01:18:53,440
"LAND OF HOPE AND GLORY" PLAYS

1233
01:20:18,480 --> 01:20:20,600
I'm sorry, madam, but you can't go in.

1234
01:20:20,600 --> 01:20:23,200
I must. It's my husband. Please.

1235
01:21:29,680 --> 01:21:31,080
Excuse me.

1236
01:21:33,000 --> 01:21:34,320
Excuse me.

1237
01:21:51,400 --> 01:21:53,240
What's happened to the iron gate, Mother?

1238
01:21:53,240 --> 01:21:56,200
It went for salvage two years ago.

1239
01:21:56,200 --> 01:21:58,000
I'll miss the squeaking of that old gate.

1240
01:21:59,200 --> 01:22:00,880
Have there been any other changes?

1241
01:22:00,880 --> 01:22:03,880
No. I kept your room exactly as it was

1242
01:22:03,880 --> 01:22:05,360
the day you went off to France.

1243
01:22:08,160 --> 01:22:10,880
Same old smell.

1244
01:22:10,880 --> 01:22:13,000
Like soap and furniture polish.

1245
01:22:14,240 --> 01:22:18,160
You come in here for a minute and I'll get you something to eat.

1246
01:22:26,640 --> 01:22:27,960
David.

1247
01:22:29,560 --> 01:22:30,800
Elspeth.

1248
01:22:33,320 --> 01:22:34,960
That last letter.

1249
01:22:36,400 --> 01:22:38,160
Your mother showed me.

1250
01:22:38,160 --> 01:22:41,520
Telling the truth about your eyes.

1251
01:22:41,520 --> 01:22:43,200
So that was the reason.

1252
01:22:43,200 --> 01:22:45,400
The reason for what?

1253
01:22:45,400 --> 01:22:47,360
For breaking our engagement.

1254
01:22:47,360 --> 01:22:49,720
But you can't go on being engaged

1255
01:22:49,720 --> 01:22:51,600
when you're not in love any longer.

1256
01:22:51,600 --> 01:22:53,600
You can't go on breaking a person's heart

1257
01:22:53,600 --> 01:22:56,160
to satisfy your own stupid pride.

1258
01:22:56,160 --> 01:22:57,920
I'm not prepared to discuss the matter.

1259
01:22:57,920 --> 01:23:01,240
Neither am I. David...

1260
01:23:02,600 --> 01:23:06,040
Why did you have to make me so dreadfully unhappy?

1261
01:23:34,680 --> 01:23:35,760
Caroline!

1262
01:23:37,440 --> 01:23:39,280
But...but what are you...

1263
01:23:39,280 --> 01:23:41,200
There were some things I left behind.

1264
01:23:42,800 --> 01:23:44,520
Caretaker let me in.

1265
01:23:44,520 --> 01:23:46,160
I had no idea.

1266
01:23:49,440 --> 01:23:50,560
I'll go now.

1267
01:23:52,480 --> 01:23:54,160
Caroline.

1268
01:23:54,160 --> 01:23:55,960
Yes, Stephen?

1269
01:23:55,960 --> 01:23:58,120
Are you all right?

1270
01:24:01,120 --> 01:24:02,520
Why are you crying?

1271
01:24:04,240 --> 01:24:06,520
Because I'm a fool.

1272
01:24:06,520 --> 01:24:09,400
Are you unhappy with Robert?

1273
01:24:10,800 --> 01:24:12,240
I'm not with Robert.

1274
01:24:13,840 --> 01:24:15,040
Oh, Stephen.

1275
01:24:16,200 --> 01:24:18,080
Why did you have to believe that letter?

1276
01:24:19,520 --> 01:24:22,160
It wasn't true? It wasn't true?!

1277
01:24:22,160 --> 01:24:24,240
No. Not then.

1278
01:24:25,360 --> 01:24:26,600
Go on.

1279
01:24:27,520 --> 01:24:28,960
When I got your letter, it was as if

1280
01:24:28,960 --> 01:24:31,800
all I'd ever believed in didn't exist anymore.

1281
01:24:31,800 --> 01:24:33,840
I didn't care what happened.

1282
01:24:33,840 --> 01:24:35,480
He was in love with you?

1283
01:24:35,480 --> 01:24:37,920
- Yes. 
- And you?

1284
01:24:37,920 --> 01:24:39,960
No.

1285
01:24:41,560 --> 01:24:43,040
Let me go now. Please.

1286
01:24:45,160 --> 01:24:46,720
Listen, Caroline.

1287
01:24:46,720 --> 01:24:50,440
There, everything seemed so... so out of proportion.

1288
01:24:50,440 --> 01:24:52,720
I think I was mad for a bit.

1289
01:24:52,720 --> 01:24:55,560
You see, I loved you so desperately.

1290
01:24:55,560 --> 01:24:57,400
Still do.

1291
01:24:57,400 --> 01:24:59,920
- Always shall. 
- Stephen...

1292
01:25:13,480 --> 01:25:14,440
Thanks, mate.

1293
01:25:17,240 --> 01:25:18,280
Thanks.

1294
01:25:18,280 --> 01:25:20,040
Well, this is it, Dai.

1295
01:25:20,040 --> 01:25:22,040
- Yes. 
- How do you feel?

1296
01:25:22,040 --> 01:25:24,160
Empty. Empty inside.

1297
01:25:24,160 --> 01:25:26,880
Me too, like it wasn't me standing here at all.

1298
01:25:26,880 --> 01:25:28,600
Come on, Dai. Let's get weaving.

1299
01:25:36,120 --> 01:25:37,480
KNOCKING

1300
01:25:45,640 --> 01:25:47,320
Hello, old girl.

1301
01:25:47,320 --> 01:25:48,880
Hello, Ted.

1302
01:25:50,880 --> 01:25:52,320
Journey all right?

1303
01:25:53,600 --> 01:25:54,840
I was seasick.

1304
01:25:56,000 --> 01:25:58,160
Stomach always was your weakness.

1305
01:26:02,600 --> 01:26:04,280
Suits you.

1306
01:26:04,280 --> 01:26:05,560
Oh, Ted.

1307
01:26:05,560 --> 01:26:06,760
There, there.

1308
01:26:07,960 --> 01:26:10,400
I can't leave Dai out in the cold like that.

1309
01:26:11,360 --> 01:26:13,480
- Oh, Dai. 
- Hello, Flo.

1310
01:26:13,480 --> 01:26:16,240
Oh, it's lovely to see you. Come on in.

1311
01:26:22,080 --> 01:26:23,560
- Where is she? 
- In here.

1312
01:26:40,880 --> 01:26:43,360
- Hello, Gwyneth. 
- Hello.

1313
01:26:43,360 --> 01:26:46,320
- Do you know who I am? 
- Yes. You're my daddy, aren't you?

1314
01:26:46,320 --> 01:26:49,120
That's it. Look.

1315
01:26:49,120 --> 01:26:51,160
I made this in the prison camp for you.

1316
01:26:53,040 --> 01:26:55,960
- Can she shut her eyes? 
- No, she can't.

1317
01:26:57,320 --> 01:27:00,040
- My doll can. 
- She's lovely.

1318
01:27:04,880 --> 01:27:05,960
So that's settled.

1319
01:27:05,960 --> 01:27:09,280
Captain Hasek reports to duty to Czech headquarters.

1320
01:27:09,280 --> 01:27:11,880
There was something I wanted to ask, sir.

1321
01:27:11,880 --> 01:27:14,720
- About Mrs Mitchell. 
- Oh, yes. Very awkward, of course.

1322
01:27:14,720 --> 01:27:17,920
Don't worry, Captain Hasek. We've got that matter in hand.

1323
01:27:17,920 --> 01:27:20,280
I wanted to suggest, sir, as it's my responsibility,

1324
01:27:20,280 --> 01:27:22,480
that if the notification of her husband's death

1325
01:27:22,480 --> 01:27:25,200
could be delayed until I've seen Mrs Mitchell myself.

1326
01:27:25,200 --> 01:27:27,440
She'll have to be told through the usual channels.

1327
01:27:27,440 --> 01:27:30,360
- Yes, sir, but in a case like this... 
- War Office will look after it.

1328
01:27:30,360 --> 01:27:34,400
Of course, if you'd like to see her off your own bat, there's nothing to stop you.

1329
01:27:34,400 --> 01:27:37,120
I see. Thank you, sir.

1330
01:27:41,840 --> 01:27:42,960
Looks like rain.

1331
01:27:45,160 --> 01:27:49,400
My dear. It's no good going on hoping.

1332
01:27:49,400 --> 01:27:50,680
You must face up to it.

1333
01:27:52,720 --> 01:27:54,280
That he won't come back?

1334
01:27:54,280 --> 01:27:55,680
That he won't come back.

1335
01:28:01,320 --> 01:28:03,360
Grandpa. It's starting to rain.

1336
01:28:03,360 --> 01:28:05,680
Come help me put the chairs in the summer house.

1337
01:28:05,680 --> 01:28:07,160
Oh, come on.

1338
01:28:07,160 --> 01:28:10,400
DOORBELL RINGS

1339
01:28:23,760 --> 01:28:25,840
Oh...

1340
01:28:25,840 --> 01:28:29,440
I'm sorry. I was expecting someone else.

1341
01:28:29,440 --> 01:28:30,920
Mrs Mitchell, I came to see you.

1342
01:28:30,920 --> 01:28:34,560
I have some news for you, of your husband.

1343
01:28:37,040 --> 01:28:38,560
Oh.

1344
01:28:38,560 --> 01:28:40,280
Come in, please.

1345
01:28:50,520 --> 01:28:51,560
What?

1346
01:28:53,720 --> 01:28:55,200
Your husband is dead.

1347
01:28:57,280 --> 01:28:58,680
Dead?

1348
01:29:00,040 --> 01:29:01,480
He was killed four years ago

1349
01:29:01,480 --> 01:29:03,640
in the fighting at Saint-Ardennie.

1350
01:29:03,640 --> 01:29:07,000
I heard from him. From the prison camp.

1351
01:29:08,200 --> 01:29:10,440
Your husband was never in that prison camp.

1352
01:29:10,440 --> 01:29:12,480
He was never a prisoner of war.

1353
01:29:12,480 --> 01:29:14,680
But...the letters...

1354
01:29:14,680 --> 01:29:16,400
I wrote those letters.

1355
01:29:18,240 --> 01:29:20,360
- You? 
- Yes.

1356
01:29:22,440 --> 01:29:24,080
But I...

1357
01:29:24,080 --> 01:29:26,040
I took these from your husband's body.

1358
01:29:26,040 --> 01:29:29,720
I took his name, his uniform, his identity.

1359
01:29:31,200 --> 01:29:34,840
For four years, I've been Geoffrey Mitchell.

1360
01:29:39,480 --> 01:29:40,680
But why?

1361
01:29:42,160 --> 01:29:44,720
To save my life. The Germans were after me.

1362
01:29:45,840 --> 01:29:48,480
- The letters? 
- Later in the camp, I had to write.

1363
01:29:48,480 --> 01:29:49,960
They suspected me.

1364
01:29:49,960 --> 01:29:52,920
If I hadn't answered your letters, they'd have been on to me.

1365
01:29:52,920 --> 01:29:55,080
You had to answer my letters.

1366
01:29:55,080 --> 01:29:56,720
I understand that. You...

1367
01:29:57,760 --> 01:29:59,800
You even had to go on writing.

1368
01:29:59,800 --> 01:30:01,240
I understand that, too.

1369
01:30:03,800 --> 01:30:06,400
Why did you have to write the way you did?

1370
01:30:09,040 --> 01:30:11,680
I believed every word you said.

1371
01:30:11,680 --> 01:30:14,440
At first, I had to make you tell me

1372
01:30:14,440 --> 01:30:16,520
as much as possible about yourself.

1373
01:30:16,520 --> 01:30:18,080
I was fighting for my life.

1374
01:30:19,800 --> 01:30:20,840
And then...

1375
01:30:22,680 --> 01:30:24,640
..I got your other letters.

1376
01:30:24,640 --> 01:30:26,200
Photos of the children.

1377
01:30:29,400 --> 01:30:31,600
Glimpses of things lost to me forever and...

1378
01:30:33,200 --> 01:30:36,400
It was as if you were offering me a new world.

1379
01:30:39,400 --> 01:30:41,840
It was easy out there to delude oneself.

1380
01:30:43,200 --> 01:30:46,760
And I believed a wonderful thing had happened.

1381
01:30:46,760 --> 01:30:48,560
My husband had left me.

1382
01:30:48,560 --> 01:30:52,240
And those letters made me believe he was mine again,

1383
01:30:52,240 --> 01:30:55,040
that everything would be as I'd hoped it would be.

1384
01:30:56,280 --> 01:30:58,440
I planned for the day he'd come home again...

1385
01:30:59,840 --> 01:31:01,280
..for a new life together.

1386
01:31:04,160 --> 01:31:06,520
What a fool I was.

1387
01:31:06,520 --> 01:31:08,320
You were still in love with him?

1388
01:31:09,800 --> 01:31:11,640
How I can tell now?

1389
01:31:13,240 --> 01:31:15,520
I know there's no excuse for what I did, but...

1390
01:31:15,520 --> 01:31:18,080
Will you go now, please?

1391
01:31:18,080 --> 01:31:21,440
You must believe that I meant what I wrote.

1392
01:31:21,440 --> 01:31:24,520
Your letters came to be my life.

1393
01:31:24,520 --> 01:31:28,000
You see, I fell in love with you.

1394
01:31:28,000 --> 01:31:33,000
It was a dream then. Now it's reality.

1395
01:31:41,320 --> 01:31:43,960
SHE SOBS

1396
01:32:16,640 --> 01:32:18,080
'I allowed myself to dream

1397
01:32:18,080 --> 01:32:21,120
'that these letters of ours could come to life.

1398
01:32:21,120 --> 01:32:23,840
'That I could see with my own eyes your home,

1399
01:32:23,840 --> 01:32:26,840
'the children, yourself.'

1400
01:33:08,600 --> 01:33:11,440
Celia, you're wanted on the telephone.

1401
01:33:11,440 --> 01:33:12,600
Who is it?

1402
01:33:12,600 --> 01:33:14,520
Captain Hasek.

1403
01:33:29,960 --> 01:33:31,880
INAUDIBLE OVER MUSIC

